animal.description:
Pedro is a male Chihuahua who is estimated to be about 2 years old and 10 pounds.  He came to our rescue as a stray. 
Pedro is timid and shy around new people and surroundings.He has a bit of an attitude and will need an experienced adopter to work with him.
He is in a foster home with other dogs and cats. The foster family will work on the basics of house and crate training, socializing and basics.
Pedro was adopted and returned as he didn't get along with the other dogs in the home.***Pedro would do Best as the SOLO pet-no other dogs in the home ***.
Pedro is one of our pets the requires a secured fenced yard as he is considered a flight risk. If he gets away, he will be impossible to catch.
All medical work is completed prior to adoption including neutering shots worming flea treatment kennel cough rabies shot micro chip and vet exam. 
Adoption fee is $150 +tax with an approved  application. 
Adoption application is available on the website www.prairiepawsrescue.com and go to the adopt link to download the application fill it out and submit

animal.description:
Charlie is a cute IG mix who’s had a bit of a rough life. She was adopted from a Chicago-area shelter at 5 years old, and was surrendered to rescue at nearly 10 years old when she wasn’t happy about the new baby in her family. In the meantime, she was diagnosed with a heart issue which requires that is well controlled with an easy daily pill.

Charlie gets along with other dogs around her size, is great with both men and women (but seems to prefer men!) and very devoted to her people. She is low key, but loves to go for walks, and would actually do fine being leash walked daily for her potty time. She really wants nothing more than a comfy dog bed and some attention.

If you’re interested in adopting our adorable Charlie, please visit our website at www.IgRescueOhio.org to submit an adoption application.

animal.description:
Hi everyone, I'm Piper! I long for love and acceptance out of life. Can you give me that? I was the runt of my litter (our mom was pure Doberman, dad unknown), and I suffered from parvo as a baby. I still have lingering side effects, which lead me to having poor coordination. My vet says my front half doesn't know what my back half is doing. I do well in areas I am accustomed to that have few hurdles for me. I like to go for walks and play. Here at the shelter, though, I bump my head a lot in small spaces (they say they are gonna get me a Bears helmet to wear, haha). I also tend to slip a lot on the floors. When we have bad weather at the shelter, I have trouble navigating the stairs into the play yards, so I tend to get knicked up sometimes. A shelter really isn't the place for a girl like me. In a home, one would barely notice any deficiencies! I would be just like a regular pup! I excel at nose work (I can find a cookie in any cardboard box!) and alerting my family to any potential danger. Squirrels are deadlier than they appear... I have a buddy at the shelter who spends lots of time with me and this is what she says: "I have been Piper's buddy for a few months now and I so hope she will find a foster home during the construction of our new shelter. I am unable to foster her myself due to the fact that my grandchildren of four, five and under, spend time at my home and it would be the same as the construction zone for Piper. My dream home for her would be on a quiet street with a front porch where she can sit with her family and continue to see that the outside world is not something to fear. What she really needs more than the dream front porch is a quiet home with a fenced back yard and baby gates for the stairs in the home, so she won't fall. She needs a family who will help her to become the confident dog that I know she has the potential to be in the future. She is so sweet and really has come a long way in the time I have spent with her. She bonded with me quickly and has begun to be less fearful out in front of the shelter. She has even gotten stronger and her gait is much steadier. I hope that someone can help this special girl." It is important to note that on the occasion I take vacations at volunteers' home, I am not known to have accidents if I get taken out regularly. I need work on basic obedience commands. Going to classes will help me with my confidence, socialization and bond with my new family. I have not been well socialized with other dogs, so I am not sure what to make of them. I am respectful and am in some puppy play groups at the shelter to help me in this regard. Since I was known to be possessive over food and toys in my old home, unfortunately, I must be the only pet. I can be a bit of a scaredy cat, and loud noises send me for under the bed, so if I am to live with kids they must be at least 12. Since I am uncoordinated, I cannot live where I would have to go up and down the stairs. I want to live a full, happy life with you. Won't you take a chance on a very special girl like me?

Please note - we always take our animals back if for some reason it doesn't work in your home so we only adopt to the following Illinois counties: Cook, DuPage, Kane, Kendall, Lake, McHenry, Will.

animal.description:
Eve is five years old, well trained and friendly with all people. 

She needs to be an only pet - she will never be a "dog park" dog, she will never have other dog friends. She is also not an "easy" dog. She's not a couch potato, though she will relax with you and she does love to snuggle. She loves all humans, adults and kids alike. She needs someone who will continue all her training that she has worked so hard on the last few years, so that she does not revert back into being leash reactive.

She needs someone who will get her sufficient exercise, understand how to properly channel her drive and take her intensity seriously. She needs a fully fenced yard that is fenced with stockade six foot fencing so there is no chance of another dog getting in or her getting out. If you can understand how to own a dog like Eve, you will have a serious GEM on your hands who will love your kids unconditionally and be a joy to have in your home.

PLEASE DO NOT INQUIRE ABOUT EVE IF:
-You have ANY other pets
-You are against crates
-You are not open to balanced training
-You live in an apartment complex where there are other dogs

Email caredogvolunteers@gmail.com


*PLEASE NOTE: All dogs are in foster care all over MA & RI. They are NOT at the cat shelter in Acushnet, which is the address listed on Petfinder. There are ONLY cats there. We do not set up meet and greets with dogs until after you've been approved to adopt. Please do not email asking us if you can come by and meet a dog the same day.*

animal.description:
Meet Marshmallow!

It's not just his adorable appearance that lent Marshmallow his name, but his ultra-soft and sweet personality when he has made a new friend. Playful, exuberant and downright giddy when playtime comes around, Marshmallow loves getting out to the yard and snuggling up with his people when they're not playing. There's nothing we love to see more than Marshmallow's smile as he has had a long journey to get to us.

We first met Marshmallow when he was found running along a local road in pretty strange circumstances. He had a muzzle on that was too tight, and another collar. Having no idea what had happened to Marshmallow before he ended up near our shelter, we set out to make sure he knew from that day forward he was going to be loved and cared for. Given how we had met him, it made sense that Marshmallow needs more time to get to know new people. Once he has settled in a new place, he is wary of strangers and needs more time to get to know someone. A potential adopter would come by the shelter a few times to get to know him and our Shelter and Behavior Manager would be able to explain in-depth how to transition Marshmallow into a home. Once he has opened up, he is an absolute gem of a dog. Marshmallow is smart, loving and affectionate all wrapped in a cute package. 

Contact the Adoptions team at (914) 273-1674 or adoptions@adoptadog,org for more information!

The first step to adopting one of our dogs is to fill out our online adoptions questionnaire located here: https://forms.gle/pnkaGTG8Cy4dgQRJ8

Riley was rescued during Hurricane Michael, in the Florida Panhandle. Riley's family lost their home and unfortunately had no where to go that would accept dogs. He was very bonded to his brother, but may not due well with new dogs. We are unsure of his background as we had very limited time with his prior owners. We believe Riley is still recovering from the shock of the hurricane, as he was inside the home as the walls collapsed. He does well indoors, is house broken and seems to be getting use to a new life here at Oscar's Cause. 

If you are interested in meeting Riley and you have other pets, we highly recommend bringing them in for a proper introduction prior to adoption. It is unknown how Riley is with cats, as we have not tested that. Riley would do best with an experienced owner, someone with history with dogs whom have been through a lot of stress.

Sweet Josie has eyes that will melt your heart. This 5-year-old Hound mix was a stray picked up by a local shelter. She is a very frightened girl who is good with other dogs and is learning to accept the love of people. Josie is currently in a home receiving lots of love and support from her fosters and several other canines. She loves to romp with her new foster siblings in the safety of their fenced backyard. That being said, the perfect home for her would be one with a fenced yard, other dogs and older children (if any) as she is nervous around sudden movements and noises.  Josie has been spayed, fully vaccinated and is heartworm positive. Not to worry though, SQ Rescue has started her treatment and will cover that expense. Please consider taking Josie in as your new family member. 

Adoption fee: (Cash/Check) $175 (Credit/Debit) $180. This includes vet care and vaccines up until adoption, spaying/neutering, and microchip. If you are interested in this wonderful pet, please complete an online application at sqrescueinc.org. Your application must be approved prior to meeting our dogs outside of our scheduled adoption events. For questions about the application process, you may call 803.223.9729 and leave a message.

Q-tip is a Chihuahua-mix. He is 11-years-old pooch who weighs 30 pounds. This handsome boy is pure white and oh, so beautiful! Q-tip or just 'Q' is a very sweet older boy. 

Q-tip just wants to lay on your lap in a blanket and be loved. What a sweet and beautiful boy! If you need to go out, Q-tip will lay on the back of the couch and look out the window waiting for your return - so be sure to leave the blinds up a bit for him to see outside.

Q-tip will love his person unconditionally, but he needs time to realize you are his person. You see, this boy came to Mostly Muttz Rescue from a situation of neglect. He needs time and consistency for him to thrive. He has been getting lots of love and structure from his foster family. 

Q is crate trained. He might whine the first few minutes but will settle after that. He is great on a leash. While walking, fast cars or trucks might startle and scare him, but he is making progress with that.

Is time, love, and stucture something you can give this boy? Do you have room in your home and heart for this special boy? You can apply to adopt Q-Tip at www.mostlymuttz.org/adoption-application/.

?OSCAR NEEDS A FOSTER OR FOREVER HOME!?

Oscar is a 3.5 year old pit bull mix who weighs 70 lbs.  Oscar was found abandoned in the country during the winter.  He was found out in the cold, emaciated.  He is now healthy and ready for his forever home.  

Oscar loves to play with toys and he loves people!  He loves going on walks and getting to say hi to everyone he passes.   He'd do well with older kids but not as well with small children since he's large and we wouldn't want him to knock them down accidentally.  

Oscar would like a home where he has an active family to occupy him and a backyard with a stockade fence.  He is such a sweet boy who just needs someone to give him a chance at a life with love and a family.  He would do best as the only dog in the home. 

Oscar is leash and crate trained.  He has probably never lived in a home before so most likely he will need assistance with house training although he does keep his kennel clean. 

Oscar is neutered, microchipped, and up-to-date on his shots.  His adoption fee is $175.

If you would like to adopt Oscar and make him a part of your family, please apply at FYDRadopt.com

Oscar is also in need of a foster home!  If you'd like to foster him, please apply at https://foreveryoursokc.org/foster-application/

animal.description:
Thank you for your interest in dog who needs a new home. Adoption can be one of the most fulfilling experiences in your life and especially in the life of your new canine companion.

A note to those looking at CPR. We have no perfect dogs - but many of our dogs have proven to be perfect for a certain someone. Our job is to find those someone's. Our most successful adopters come to CPR not because they want a dog. They come to us because they want to give a dog a home. We urge all of our potential adopters not to fall in love with a picture. While we like to know what you like in looks, a dog is more than a pretty face. Our goal is to match you with the best possible pet for you and your home. We want to create furever families.

Our descriptions contain all that we know about this dog today. We'll update as more information is known.

Are you looking to adopt within the next 30 days? If so please visit our webpage at www.carolinapoodlerescue.org and complete the application. You'll find it in the menu on the left hand side. You'll also find a total listing of all our dogs available.

Just browsing but interested in poodles and poodle mixes? Please drop a note to applications@carolinapoodlerescue.org with your name, address and phone # and email. We'll add you to our mailing list.

thanks
the CPR Adoption team

Date into Rescue: 7/8/18
Reason for being in rescue: Stray, found at CPR employee's house

Foster location: Foster Home in Pacolet, SC
Special Needs? This dog was lightly heartworm positive when he came in. We had him on a monthly preventative and is now heartworm free!!!
Weight: Estimated 52 lbs
Height: est 24" at the shoulder
Spayed/Neutered: Yes

Adoption Fee: $200

Fence needed? Yes, Dawson is a young, large breed dog and needs room to play. He also needs the security of a fence that he can not escape. Dawson likes to go on walk about all by himself and has to be watched. Dawson can open gates with his nose. You have to stay with him in the yard and your gates must have clips on them to keep this smart guy from taking himself out of the yard. He does not climb or dig out of his own yard. He is in a a 5' high farm fence and this happily contains him.

What kind of home would be best for me? Dawson has a puppy personality and needs basic training. He would do best in a home with no small animals. He is living with two toy poodles and doing well but his foster mom is very dog savvy and knows how to keep his energy channeled in the right direction. He would love a larger dog to play with. Oreo S'moreo, also up for adoption, is his BFF in the play yards. Dawson is used to a lot of human interaction and needs someone who is not going to leave him in a crate more than 2 hours at a time. He gets bored easily and he will figure out how to escape. A best case scenario would a home school family with children over 8 years old or a recent retiree who is looking for a best buddy and has lots of time to spend.

What is my personality like? Dawson is believed to be a Shepherd/Husky mix and is only estimated to be around 1 year old. Dawson is a happy go lucky guy always looking for someone to give hugs to. He doesn't think twice about sticking his paw up for hand shakes or jumping on you for nose kisses. He is problem solving smart, and all that intelligence needs to be coached and directed. He needs a job and he will thrive. He's not a couch potato kind of guy.

Dawson has a very high energy level. His foster mom's fondest wish for him is someone retired from police work or military work with canines and that has had much dog training experience and wants to keep their skills sharp. Dawson would absolutely thrive with someone who wanted to try many of the canine activities available today. His foster mom thinks he would thrive at nosework. She also thinks he would enjoy lure coursing and barn hunting and maybe even weight pulling.

He has a strong prey drive and a nose that knows all. He could also do great with a fun, active family to play with or with an outdoors kind of person who runs, hikes, and camps. We could see Dawson hiking the Appalachian Trail and being Mr. Adventure (but always on leash). So far he has gotten along with the dogs that he has came into contact with, but is too rough and curious for very small animals. He walks well on a leash using a front lead harness. With a regular harness he would pull. He loves to ride in a car and never gets car sick. He is used to travelling in a seat belt harness. We know this guy will move his way into a families heart very quickly, given the chance!

How do I act when I first meet new people? He loves strangers, he loves them so much he even walked up and introduced himself to our groomer when he was a stray. That got him a foster home.

Other tips and tidbits: Estimated Birthdate: 7/8/2017. Dawson is in a foster home with our groomer. She is teaching him the joys of sleeping in the bed, riding in the car and going to Petco to shop. He has learned sit, shake and down. He is reacting very well to all this teaching and mastering his new skills. Dawson comes to the farm each day that his foster mom works to socialize with other dogs and romp and play in our fields. He is getting a well rounded education on how to be a great pet.

Dawson would be destructive if left unsupervised in the house. Destructive fun includes getting into the trash, he stares hard at the guinea pigs that he can't reach. He will counter surf. Latest theft was a bag of taco shells when his foster mom was grocery shopping. He needs a strong crate to hold him. He's happy in a plastic heavy duty vari kennel with a chewy while you are out grocery shopping or otherwise engaged.

House trained? Dawson is in a foster home and he has never had an accident in the house. He is supervised at all times when he is in the house. His foster mom says he does not offer to life his leg and mark ever. He sleeps sounding but if his family gets up to go potty in the middle of the night, he's a good boy and goes outside, too. Dogs can be house trained if they are in the right environment and are allowed to follow a schedule as long as a physical reason doesn't keep them from being trained. A dog house trained in my home may not be in yours. We will help you teach your new dog this necessary skill and based on your schedule.

Please note - we do not ship dogs. If you are interested in adopting, please take a look at the distance between the foster home location and your location and make sure you are willing to make that trip. Most of our dogs are at our farm in Pacolet, South Carolina.

To apply, please visit our webpage at www.carolinapoodlerescue.org and visit the tab on the left that directions you to the online application.

Please note that when screening applications, we look at the entire home and then make suggestions based on what would be a good fit for your home. You are not being screened for a specific dog although we are looking to see what type of dog interests you - poodles or non poodles, color, age, etc. Others here may be a better fit for you. It is very difficult to get to know a living animal from a picture and a short description. Since we are constantly getting in new dogs, this may be a dog not in our listings yet. We want you to be very happy with your new companion and will make suggestions based on what you tell us about you.

Thank you for considering CPR.

animal.description:
Brooke has an unusual past.  She was rescued from Afghanistan as a puppy and made her way to the US to our sanctuary!  She is a sight-hound mix and has all the wonderful attributes that they possess.  If you would like a dog that can run like the wind then she is the dog for you!  An ancient breed, they were the hunting dogs and Brooke certainly thinks she should be queen!

This speed and the unusual ability to see far into the distance necessitates a fenced in yard or a place that is fenced where she can stretch those long legs of hers!  She walks well on leash but likes to be able to feel the wind in her fur.

We have asked Brooke what she would like in her very own home and she feels she would like an adult home who have dog experience.   She also requests that she be the only animal in the home!   The fenced in yard is a plus, lots of toys to enjoy and destuff, her very own bed, and people who love her sensitive side!

To learn more about this absolutely gorgeous gal, call Our Companions Animal Rescue at 242-9999 or e-mail daryl@ourcompanions.org


~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~All of the pets promoted by Our Companions Animal Rescue are located in CT.  As such we wish to adopt animals into homes in the greater CT area.  Pets are in various locations so we request that an appointment is made to meet with a specific pet we are advertising. Contact the person listed on the pet’s profile to find out more about our adoption process for a specific pet or e-mail Helpline@ourcompanions.org for general inquiries.

animal.description:
Pupdate: Recently we learned Gizmo's tail was blocking her bowels. The recommendation was to remove the tail and hope for normal bowel function. Her tail was removed July 29, 2020 and she is all healed up on the outside. The goal now is for her to have predictable, easy to clean bowel movements, but, without her tail in the way, she can now wear toddler diapers if she needs to go somewhere. We know she is improving because she keeps herself pretty clean, whereas last year, she didn't even know she had a backside!

Pupdate: Gizmo has been to several follow up appointments with her neurologist and has made progress each time. In January 2020, she saw the heart specialist again. She still has a class 3 murmur but is continuing to do well.

Update: Gizmo continues to improve and we hope someday soon, she will have control over her potty habits. Until then, we wait and pray and hope.

Update - Gizmo's post op check up ad staples removal went well. She seems like she is improving and can't wait to be active again.

Update: Gizmo has surgery on 7/24/19 to correct her tethered spinal cord and close the hole in her spinal column. During her pre-examination the vets found she now has a class 3 heart murmur caused by a malformation and leaflet tethering in her left ventricle. Gizmo is just a year old! He wants to start her on heart medication and monitor her every 6 months to see if any symptoms present. We have a post-op foster for her & she will be on 6 weeks crate rest and then have several check ups with the surgeons at VCA & then we really hope and pray she finds a forever home! We also hope and pray the surgery accomplished the goal of giving her control of her back end. Prayers for tail wags and normalacy!

Update: Gizmo had an MRI on Dec 5, 2018. She has a hole in her spinal column which has allowed her spinal cord to attch itself to muscle outside the spinal column. The good news is she can probably have surgery and be healed. The bad news is we are in the red for $2500 on her medical expenses so far and surgery could run another $4500 or more.

We were asked to help her when her mom's family couldn't. Her tail doesn't move and her back legs are weak. We paid a vet visit to get a referral to the neurologist in a nearby city and she saw the specialist twice. Gizmo could be adopted by a family who understands her needs and will get her to her appointments as needed. She is crate trained and a happy girl who walks well on a leash. She gets along with other dogs of all sizes and hasn't seemed interested in cats. She adores people and is very loving at all times. We know there is a special family out there for this special girl.
We work with many rescues and strive to find every rescued dog in our care a great home. Sometimes that means transferring that pet to another location where adoption may be more likely. We currently have partners in New York, Pennsylvania, and Vermont.

If you are interesting in meeting any of our pets, the process is to complete an application. It can be downloaded as a pdf document from our website and submitted by email to WindyRidgeRescue@gmail.com as a scanned document or as photos OR can be completed entirely online. Both links are in the header of our website.

Because we are foster based, we require an approved application to schedule a meet and greet. We feel that is fair to our fosters and rescues so every meet and greet can result in an adoption.

We do not have set adoption fees for dogs, but hope adopters will donate generously so we can rescue more. The medical care for every dog can easily exceed the adoption donation. Average adoption fees for dogs in the area range from $175 up to $450.

We ask for a minimum adoption donation of $50 for cats regardless of age. Each cat is up to date on vaccinations, dewormer, and microchipped. Larger donations are always welcome so we can rescue more. Medical care for each cat easily exceeds the minimum donation.

As with every rescue, our resources are limited and the need for rescue help is unlimited. Your generosity helps us to rescue more.

Adopting or fostering for a rescue frees up a space where a new rescue can reside.

If you can't adopt or foster, than please consider donating.
2/2/21 3:50 PM

animal.description: Luna and Star were found outside of town.  They were skittish and did not want to come to anyone to be caught-especially Star.  No one ever claimed them from animal control.  These two female Lab/Shepherds have no background information and their past is a mystery.  Luna is the yellow one and her age is estimated to be about 2 1/2 years old.  Star is the black and tan one and is thought to be a little older at 4 years old.  Both of them weigh just over 60 pounds.  Luna is more outgoing with people and can be quite playful with people once she knows them.  Star takes more time to warm up to a person and new surroundings, but she can also be playful, especially with Luna.  Both girls keep their kennels clean and they enjoy toys, treats, and playing outside in our fenced area.  Luna is learning to be on a leash, but Star still just refuses to move. For this reason, a fenced yard is needed for Star to go out into for potty time. Star is very dependent on Luna and will follow her.  The girls need to be adopted together!  These two are both spayed, vaccinated, heartworm negative, and ready to move on!  All they need is a very patient owner that can continue their socialization.

animal.description:
Jodi is a super sweet Catahoula-Black Mouth Cur mix around 7 years old. This precious, smiling girl was found under a tool shed with her 11 3-week old babies. She had a very badly broken leg and eye sight loss with head trauma. Momma Jodi had been abandoned by her owner and, soon after, was hit by a car out on a busy rural road. Calm, laidback, and quiet, Jodi loves everything there is in life - including people - and she is very friendly to everyone she meets without being pushy or ill-mannered. She will need verbalizarion when approaching her due tonight loss.

This Rescue tracked back to breeder and found out Jodi was trained as a rig dog for hog hunting. She has lost that ability due to her injuries.  Momma Jodi is a perfectly behaved, gentle and loving lady and she even knows some commands. She gets along great with adults, children, and other dogs. Jodi is housebroken, crate-trained, up-to-date on vaccinations, spayed, and microchipped.

Jodi is ready for a calm and laid back home.  Will she work well in yours?

animal.description:
Do you love the beauty of strength, and a rainbow at the end of a massive storm? If so, then this 56 pounds of pure love, five year old, American Bulldog may just be your soulmate! Storm is mighty in strength and stature as his name would suggest yet is a big goofball with soulful eyes who will be your absolute best friend given the chance. Storm is an active dog who loves to hike and would be an awesome adventurer with a seasoned dog handler. Even though this guy was rescued off the streets in pretty rough shape, he immediately responded to human companionship and is oh so eager to please – especially if you are offering a treat! Storm will impress you with his tricks and is great with dogs of all sizes with a proper intro. He needs a great leader who can continue working on his training to help him fulfill his calling as a breed ambassador. Just look at this guy! He is ready and waiting to be a part of your very active lifestyle. 

If you're interested in adopting this pet please fill out our matchmaking questionnaire (www.rescuefromthehart.org).  We are volunteer based and will do our best to get back to you within 72 hours.  Please do not call as our phone is intended for emergencies only. If we feel that one of our dogs is a good match we will set up a private meet and greet  We do not have a physical location where you can come and meet all the dogs at once, so meet and greets may take a little time to coordinate.  Our requested adoption donation is $350 and all adopters are required to fill out an adoption agreement.

animal.description:
Hello! My name is Kenzi. I have been with TIRR Rescue since 2010.
?
I’ve been to a few homes during my time with TIRR, but none of them quite worked out. I have some separation anxiety and ended up being just a little too much for my adopters. As such, I would do best in a home with someone who isn’t gone very often.
?
I’m really a sweet girl who just wants to love and be loved. I especially like hanging out with kids, and babies don’t bother me at all. I also get along well with little dogs and cats. I have basic obedience and would love to spend time with you while you teach me more tricks and commands!
?
If you think you might be my forever family, be sure to contact my rescue people!

~~~~

PERSONALITY:
Kenzi is an affectionate girl who loves everyone. She has great confidence, allowing her to handle any situation with aplomb. She does have some separation anxiety, so she would do best with a family that is either home most of the time or takes her with them. She is still very active and loves to run and play. One of her favorite pastimes is chewing on sticks or tree stumps.

~~~~

To learn more about Kenzi, please visit tirrrescue.org/kenzi.

animal.description:
Hey, everyone!  My name is Buda - short for Boudica - and I've been at TIRR Rescue since 2013.

When I was young, a nice man saved me from the shelter and brought me to TIRR Rescue in the hopes they could find me a great forever home.  I haven't found one yet, but I'm still hopeful!

I'm good with other big dogs and like to wrestle, especially with my pal Poncho.  I absolutely love my people and am always excited to see them.  I can be pretty active, but I also enjoy just laying around in my dog house - or under it - keeping cool.  I would make a great jogging or walking buddy; it would help me burn off some of my excess energy.  I really like to dig, as you can see in one of the pictures above, so it would be really nice if I could have a yard with a dedicated digging space for me!

I'd love to meet some new people, so you should definitely come see me.  If you think you could be next forever home, be sure to talk to my rescue people!

~~~~

PERSONALITY:
Buda is a sweet girl.  She loves to play and wrestle but also loves to lay around and chill, preferably with a soft, stuffed toy.  While she does well with most dogs, she sometimes gets annoyed with little dogs and is best not left unsupervised with them.  She loves her people and is always excited to see them.  She would make a good walking partner, but she will also need a dedicated digging area so she can pass time doing one of her favorite activities without ruining the yard.  However, Buda really just wants a family that will love on her.

~~~~

To learn more about Buda, please visit tirrrescue.org/buda.

animal.description: Reo has been in ARLO's care for over 1,000 days!! Why does she keep getting over-looked? We know the right home for Reo is out there. Help us find it! Reo is a doll! She came from the Okemah pound in Sept 2016. Your donations helped us save her! Reo is a young female Pit Bull Terrier, 3 years old now. She weighs right at 50 lbs. She is black with beautiful white markings and a white tip on her tail. She loves to play and run. She is a cuddle bug too! She likes to be in your lap and give kisses :) She gets along with other dogs and loves to play. She has played with many foster dogs at her current foster home and has done great with all ages and sizes. She is a real sweetheart and will make someone a very loyal companion. She is scared of thunder. She has not lived with cats or kids. She does good with older kids. Small ones in her face makes her nervous. Reo is spayed, utd on vaccinations, heartworm negative and on monthly prevention, flea and tick free and microchipped. Her adoption fee is reduced to $50. We desperately want to get Reo into a home of her own. She has waited way too long. Please share and help Reo! Apply online at www.arlorescue.org. Once approved we will set up a time to meet Reo.

animal.description: Meet Honey! She is one of our long-time residents. She has been with us since Dec 2017. It is time for Honey to have a family of her own. Honey came to us terrified, timid, and obviously had known nothing but hate most of her life. She would hide in her house, cower down when we would go to pet her. It took several weeks for Honey to relax. She finally decided she enjoyed belly rubs and butt scratches. She would stand to be petted and she was starting to trust her small circle of people. She was smiling and carrying herself with joy again. Honey is good with other dogs. She is a 4 year old Staffordshire Terrier. She is short and stout. She is still shy of new people and things and takes time to warm up. We want nothing more than a loving home for Honey. She would probably do best in a quieter home, no small children with someone willing to be patient with Honey. Adoption fee is reduced to $50. This includes her spay, deworming, vaccinations, flea/tick control, heartworm neg and started on monthly prevention and microchip. Apply to adopt at www.arlorescue.org

Prior to adoption each dog is spayed or neutered, tested for heartworm (if appropriate), started on a heartworm preventative, tested for Ehrlichia and Lymes disease (both are carried by ticks), examined for external parasites and treated with a monthly preventative, vaccinated for DHLP, Bordatella, and rabies (unless the puppy is too young), dewormed, microchipped, and receives 30 of free ShelterCare Health Insurance.

Humane Society staff and volunteers who work with the animals have gotten to know them during their stay with us and can give you information about their personalities and habits. Our Adoption Counselors will assist you in selecting an animal who will fit into your family. We can provide you with a wealth of information on caring for your new pet. Just ask! That's what we're here for!  

Please try to get your Adoption Application to us before coming to look. This way, we can help determine which will be the best match for you, your family, and your lifestyle with the least amount of stress for everyone concerned. If we don't currently have any dogs that would make a good addition to your family, we can keep your application on file and call you if one comes in that's a good candidate!

animal.description:
Meet darling Rusty, a young (about three years) loving boy who wants to please. He's had some basic training and tries hard to do his best! He's great friends with our other Misfit dogs, walks well in harness, and is alert and always checking with you to see what's next! He is a cautious first-time greeter. He wants to sniff you and hear your voice and think a bit about who you might be before he relaxes into the love sponge he really is inside. He may have had some bad prior experiences with strange men, so go slow at first meeting. Kennel and house trained, he loves people, and uses his Mind Toys (rubber chewy toys with treats inside) to great effect. He's a very smart dog and needs someone who can be firmly consistent with love and training. He just wants you to love him!

He enjoys car rides and will just lay down and enjoy the motion.

Rusty was dumped at the boat ramp at Lake Nacogdoches with a choke collar that would barely turn and was zip tied on. He would just sit by the dumpster and wait for his person to return. 

Heartworm NEGATIVE. He is up to date on vaccinations and on HW prevention. 
Weight 61 pounds.
Age approximately 1-2 years old. 

Rusty is like the energizer bunny. You can NOT wear him out. He loves loves tearing across the yard for a tossed tennis ball. If you are looking for a couch potato friend, he would NOT fit the bill. He would love to share a home with another high energy dog that would say yes to "chase me". Because he is high energy, and needs firm reminders NOT to jump on you, he  would be best suited in a home with older children.

Nimbus is a handsome 4 year old male with special needs in regard to his personality. We are looking for some very specific things in an adoptive home due to his shy and skittish behavior. Nimbus has a flight history (6 months on the run before being trapped) before coming to our program and although he has improved a lot socially over time, he still panics at change in the routine and social circle he has come to know. We would like to find an adopter close enough who can visit him multiple times to build some trust before adoption. A few specifics about Nimbus:
-He should do well with a well socialized, dog friendly, large breed female canine companion. 
-He walks well on leash unless startled, has learned to ride well and handles well at the vet and groomer. 
-Once aquainted he loves hugs and attention.
-He will require house training and work on some marking behavior. 
-Adult only home with rescue baggage experienced adopter willing to work with him to become the best he can be. 
-Securely fenced yard no less than 5 feet in height for safe yard time.

If you think you could be the the special adopter Nimbus needs please contact us by email for more information.

animal.description:
Update: (2-11-20) Ryker has spent quite a while living at the shelter at this point and has deemed his kennel his safe place. He growls and barks at people who visit him while he is in his kennel. However, once taken out he is usually very loving to the people he's met. He has even allowed a volunteer to walk him only meeting the volunteer at that point and there were no issues at all. He was happy and enjoying his time outside of the shelter. He will just need a home without small children or any other pets.

Ryker came in on 9-12-18. He had such severe injuries that we thought he had been bit by a car. Upon Vet examination, it was determined that he was actually a victim of a dog attack. He had found a forever home at first to heal and connect with his forever family in the mean time. However, within a week we had found out that he didn't do well with the adopter's 6 month old child. At that point, it was decided that it was better for him to come back to the shelter to find another forever home. He did have a problem with digging out of fences so he would need a home where he couldn't dig out or isn't left outside unattended. He does great with older children and is just a total love bug. He loves to climb in your lap and give hugs. Now that he is all healed, he needs to find his own forever family to love.

There is a $65 fee for adopting one of our male dogs/puppies or a $75 fee for adopting one of our female dogs/puppies. The fee helps cover the Spay/Neuter vouchers and the Rabies Vaccine voucher. Please look at our home page for more information about a adopting a new friend.

animal.description:
Hello there and welcome to my Petfinder page. I am Mars Barkley and I am looking for a home to call my own. I am looking for a forever place and someone to love. Let me know if you think we could be a great match.

Here’s my stats:
Possible Breed:  Shih Tzu/Lhasa Apso 
Gender:  I’m a boy pup
Colors:  Classic black and white
Age:  The vet says about 9 years young
Weight:  Around 18 pounds

Ideal Home:  I would be fine as an only dog, and I can live with other male dogs too.

Now for more good stuff!-
Mars is a laid-back boy. Some might even call him a couch potato, but he does get down from the couch and play from time to time! He is more of an independent boy, though he does still like to cuddle too.

Mars gets along with both the boy and older girl pups in his foster home. He especially likes to play with the bigger dog who lives there. He doesn’t really play with toys very often. He does enjoy chewing on hard bones. Mars walks great on a leash and really enjoys going for walks with you. He rides well in the car and he does well hanging out in a crate.

He can be a bit grumpy sometimes when you want him to do something, he doesn’t want to do. He will growl and snap, so an experienced dog owner is best. Because of this he must go into a home with no kids under 16.

Like many other Tzu and Lhasa pups, Mars has dry eye. He gets drops twice a day. We believe he has some limited vision due to this issue. 
His foster family says, “Mars prefers men, He even feel asleep on his foster dad’s lap the other day.”

For more information, email my foster mom at mel65shot@gmail.com. Start the process of adopting me or one of the other pups by filling out the application found at www.shihtzu-rescue.com. 

PS. I've had ALL my vetting, and oh boy, it was a lot. Here's what I had done:
Distemper/Parvo shots – TWICE. One shot doesn't cut it.
Bordetella shots - ALSO TWICE. 
Spay/Neuter-of course.
A fecal exam so I don't have any bad worms. Treatment if I do.
A heartworm test. Treatment if I am positive for heart worms
BLOODWORK to make sure my liver and kidneys are working well, because you know, we doggies often have issues in the liver and kidneys.
A DENTAL exam AND cleaning if I needed it- yep, all my toofies are checked out.
See, that's a LOT. Ask your vet - that's a LOT.
animal.name: Mars Barkley

animal.description:
Please meet "Bubbles", aka "Tonka" (built like a truck), "Dolly Parton" (big chest and wide smile), and "Fiona-princess". Bubbles is an energetic, enthusiastic love-machine. She is the most cuddly and affectionate dog I've ever met. She loves to lay her chin on your chest and gaze into your eyes.

Bubs is a Boxer/Bulldog/Terrier/Ridgeback-ish? mix of something. She is low to the ground but quick and strong. 52 pounds of love and about 4 years old!

Smart. Stubborn. Sweet. Funny. Snorty...And from a color perspective has the most beautiful tones of brown. She has chocolate brown eye liner and her eyes are the color of warm whiskey.

Bubs is looking for a great home. She HAS to be the only dog. She is great on a leash and loves short walks. She loves to run zoomies in the backyard (do not recommend these in the house!) and is a great watch dog. We believe she could be taught to skateboard, surf, kayak, carry a pack, do therapy work (with a bit more training). She is up for anything.

Bubbles needs to be with her people. She loves people. She is a really special girl and hoping to find a great, loving home. 

We are a RESCUE GROUP, not a shelter, and all of our animals are in foster homes. To start the adoption process, email us at adoptions@earstexas.org requesting an application. Submitting an application does not commit you in any way, but helps us make the best match between people and our available dogs. Your current or past dogs must be inside dogs who have been spayed/neutered and are on heartworm prevention.

All of the dogs in our program are inside dogs and are completely vetted including all vaccinations, spayed/neutered, free of internal parasites, microchipped, heartworm negative and on prevention before adoption. Our adoption process includes an application, check of vet records or personal references, interview, neutral site meet & greet with the dog and your family, and a home visit.

animal.description:
Do you want to adopt me? Just go to www.dogsasfamily.org and fill out an adoption application. We do not ship our dogs and all adoptions are completed in person in the Oklahoma City, Oklahoma area.
Update 1/2019 I did it! I have graduated from a training program. I am leash, house, agility course and crate trained. I know my basic commands and a few tricks too. Adopt me now so we can continue to work on my manners together.
Hello. My name is Frodo. I am male over nine years old that weighs about 21 pounds. I am a pinscher mix or at least that is my best guess. I came to the rescue with my two fur sisters after mom couldn't take care of us anymore. I know she loved us but sometimes life just happens and we are forced to deal with change. Both of my sisters are already in new homes so I am looking for a family for me.I consider myself an easy going guy although I will announce anyone at the door or a strange noise. I like most other dogs and cats. I haven't been around a lot of children but if they are at least school age I don't think we would have a problem. I am housebroken so I can easily live inside with you. I do want you to know I may be older but I still love to run and play in the fenced yard when I go outside. Sometimes I get too excited and jump up and down. Hopefully you like that excitement to see you and can love me anyways.I have been neutered, vaccinated and microchipped. I have had my teeth cleaned with a few extractions done. My adoption fee is 100.00. So now all you have to do is go to dogsasfamily.org and fill out the adoption application for Frodo. You and I could make a great family. Hope to meet you soon.

animal.description:
Friends to the Forlorn
Adopt-a-BullBreed: American Staffordshire Terrier
Gender: Male
Estimated Date of Birth: December 23, 2017
Size: 68 lbs
Location: Marietta, GA

RESCUING CAMO
Camo ended up at Henry County Animal Control where pit bulls are not adopted out to the public. Lucky for him, FTTF has some amazing foster families! Camo was on a foster to adopt with a family, but they decided their teenager was not pulling her weight when it came to taking care of him so they returned him. Camo had no problem adjusting to a new foster home with dogs he had never met before. This guy is solid!

ABOUT CAMO
Camo is a fantastic, goofy boy. A Wisdom Panel DNA test revealed that he is 100% American Staffordshire Terrier. He has a medium energy level and is well-behaved in the home. He loves to play a good game of fetch as it's his all-time favorite activity. Seriously, the ball is life! Although he is not overly demanding in his exercise requirements, he does benefit from a bit of daily exercise. A simple 15 minute session of fetch with a Chuck-It is enough to keep him happy. He actually seems to enjoy (and is quite good at) walking on the treadmill too. Camo also loves toys and will entertain himself for hours with a plain and simple Kong. He still thinks he is a small puppy and is not aware of his massive size, but he is a super-snuggler and will happily lounge on the sofa with his family. He loves to roughhouse with doggie foster siblings and he even takes correction from the bossier lady in the home, however he is not suited for a home with cats or children under 16 years old. He is rocking his house-manners and "Good Boy" is his favorite phrase to hear aside from "Are You Hungry" or "Play Ball." Without daily exercise, a state of playful excitement is easily incited where he gets extra silly and boisterous. This is when his foster mom refers to him as "Wreck-It-Ralph." He thrives on firm, consistent boundaries, but he does listen to direction and he will need a savvy owner with strong leadership skills. Camo can be a bit sensitive so a stern voice correction is all he needs to put his listening ears on. He knows he is not allowed in the kitchen when food is being prepared so with a finger snap he is quick to exit and sit at the boundary. His foster mom tries to discourage begging too so he will also get in his bed or out of the room when people are eating. He is crate-trained and housebroken and requires a 6 foot, privacy fenced yard. Just call him Mister Personality - everyone that meets him falls in love! This goober-face is just a big, mushy, enthusiastic puppy who is looking for a forever family to call his own.

Camo has been eating Hills Science Diet Sensitive Stomach & Skin Dry Dog Food. It is not a prescription diet and can be ordered on Chewy or purchased from any pet store. The NutriSource food eaten by the other dogs in our program was a tad bit rich for him and he had loose poops. There are likely other foods he would do well on, this was just the first alternative we tried. Camo also takes 1 Apoquel tablet a day to keep his environmental allergies at bay. We just toss it in his bowl with his dinner and he eats it - easy!

Follow Camo on Facebook: https://www.facebook.com/findingforeverfttf

Photo Album of Camo: https://www.facebook.com/media/set/?set=a.2072989432759212&type=1&l=9b3b11764c

Our adoption fee is $300. All dogs are current on vaccinations, spayed or neutered, micro-chipped, on heartworm prevention, and fed premium grain-free food.www.savingpitbulls.org

animal.description:
Loyal, ObedientLoyalty, Intelligence, Handsome, Protective, and Active.

Blue is a 6-year-old Blue Nose Staffie Mix. He is a gorgeous, compact, and muscular boy weighing approximately 60 pounds. If you are looking for a pup who enjoys taking walks as he does chilling on the couch this boy is for you.

Blue was given up by his family two years ago due to a divorce and since then has bounced around between a few homes. He has been to training and is incredibly smart and loyal. Blue does best in an environment where there is one person that he can rely upon. He does not like a busy household where new people coming and going. Blue enjoys affection, giving kisses, and being near his family. He has lived with both female and male fosters and does great with both.

Blue has lived in an apartment setting as well as a home. He will do best with a strong owner who can give him the guidance that he needs. He is loyal and obedient. He thrives with discipline, exercise, and love. Blue will do best with a person who understands that he requires reassurance. Blue loves the water, loves to go on walks and hikes.

Blue needs a quiet place to call home where he can just be himself. He is crate trained, doesn't require a yard as long as he can go for walks. Come meet Blue you will fall in love with this boy. To set up a meet and greet please submit a completed adoption application at doggiebonez.com. He is also on all of our social media pages IG: @Doggie_Bonez_Inc_ and Facebook: Doggie Bonez.

If adoption isn't an option, please consider fostering one of our pups. We are a volunteer-run non-profit dog rescue and always welcome new short and/or long term doggie foster families. We greatly appreciate the help and time of our fosters. You provide all the love, comfort, and safety of a home and we supply you with everything else you may need, dog food, dog bed, toys, medical attention (if needed), etc. If you are interested please visit www.doggiebonez.com to see all of our available dogs who need a foster family while waiting for their fur-ever home and complete the foster application.

animal.description:
"Hi! I'm Francesca and I'm just waiting for you to fall in love with me! I'm all about the people - snuggling with my humans is my favorite activity! I live to make people happy and getting a big kiss and a treat is my ultimate reward. How can you not love my sweet eyes and wiggly butt? In my dream home, I'd be the only dog so I could be queen of your heart. While I love every person I've ever met, other dogs aren't my thing and I'd prefer not to be around them. But if you've got a home with a yard and a couch to cuddle on, I've got an endless supply of kisses and love for you. One kiss and you'll be hooked on me forever!"

This special girl is a total love, but she wants you all to herself and cannot go to a home with other animals. Francesca is an absolute people pleaser and when it comes to humans is a social butterfly. It's hard to not give in to those deep eyes, squish and that wiggle butt! Francesca is part of our enrichment program and has stolen the hearts of our volunteers. In the program she is learning basic manners as she awaits her fur-ever home. Her ideal home is active, but understanding that she does not get along well with other dogs. She would thrive in an environment with with a yard and a place where walking her will not lead to running into too many other dogs (apartments, downtown city etc.) and someone willing to give her a little training and guidance. This goofball would give you a shower with her kisses if you let her. She is the perfect balance of a playful wild child and cuddle bug who will curl up with you at the end of the day to relax.

Find out how to meet Francesca by giving us a call at 410-268-4388.

animal.description:
I only want you, baby!

Are you a magician? Because whenever I see you, everyone else disappears!

Hey there! My name is Cali, and I am a strong, loving woman. I get very excited, and am kinda all over the place when I first meet a new person, but once you give me a chance, and let me know you are mine, I will love you fur-ever! I am a loyal, passionate girl, and I expect the same from you. I don't like to share with other animals! You will be my moon and my stars, is it so bad that I want the same level of dedication from you? I love so deeply that I am happy to just cuddle and stare lovingly into your eyes for hours.

Greatest asset: I am super goofy! I'll have you laughing for hours!

Biggest flaw: Like I said, I don't like to share. If you are mine, you are ONLY mine (at least as far as other animals go. I'm cool with other humans).

Theme song: I Only Have Eyes For You, The Flamingos

Looking for a long term commitment?: Yes, please! I've been single for about 3 years now.

Hobbies: Beyond staring into your soul through your eyes? I like tug-of-war, walks, and cuddles. Lots of cuddles!

Ideal Partner: An experienced dog parent who is willing to adapt to my needs and love me for who I am, flaws and all.

Zulu is a happy, active, spunky young mixed breed female with a short white coat and brown patches. Zulu would prefer a home without children and other pets because she wants you all to herself. She loves to play and for a small/medium sized dog, she's quite muscular and athletic. She would love a human that will take her camping, hiking, or even casual daily walking and then come home to snuggle with.

Zulu is very smart and loves enrichment activities, such as puzzles, and will amaze you with her focus and problem solving skills. Zulu even loves swimming, but watch out as she will try to "save" you if you are swimming with her! Worried you can't keep up with this active girl? Don't worry! Zulu has been trained to run on a treadmill and actually needs more mental stimulation than she does physical exertion. Zulu will keep you entertained with her antics! She also loves to play fetch!

Do you need a playful, entertaining, wacky partner to navigate through this equally crazy life? Then Zulu is waiting for you!

animal.description:
Mako’s past has been anything but easy. Adopted out of our rescue at 13 weeks old, he was returned 2 years later. We have come to learn that in his time in his first adoptive home he was tormented by one of the children there. He had Nerf guns shot at him and was being provoked daily to attack. Unfortunately, Mako had a few incidents where he did lash out at the child. So, the answer was to put a shock collar on him to attempt to stop his behavior. As many should know this was the worst thing possible for him. He was scared, insecure and was being punished for protecting himself. Once back in our care in the loving foster home that raised him from an 11-day old puppy the shock collar was removed and thrown away. After many weeks of building trust Mako is finally relaxing and showing us what a sweet boy he really is. He adores his foster mom and dad and is learning daily from his foster skin siblings that not all children are going to try to hurt him. He enjoys playing with other dogs and is great with cats. Mako is kennel trained and house broken. He LOVES going for walks, car rides and playing tug of war. Mako’s forever home will need to have NO CHILDREN for his protection. He needs a family that will give him time to adjust and build trust. He needs to not be pushed and let him take things at his own pace. Mako needs a mom or dad that will be the alpha and let him know that he will be protected. Once he figures this out, he will become your shadow and the goofiest, most loyal dog you have ever met. Mako is the pot of gold at the end of the rainbow. Let the storm pass and the love he will give you will last a lifetime!

A DNA test was done on one of his siblings and Mako is a German Shepherd, Greyhound, ChowChow, Alaskan Malamute, AmStaff, Rottweiler, hound mix. He is built like a Greyhound, has the coat of a GSD and the most adorable ears of a ChowChow. He weighs around 67 pounds and is a true Heinze 57 dog!



Little did the rescuers know when they found an injured dog on the side of the road that in the nearby cornfield, she would be hiding a little secret. Eight little secrets to be exact! At only two days old Mako and his siblings were rescued from a life of uncertainty to be given a life hope with Hands, Hearths and Paws. Born on 8/19/2018 Mako is a typical happy little boy. A DNA test was done on one of his siblings and the results were 12.5% Alaskan Malamute, 12.5% German Shepherd Dog, 12.5% ChowChow, 12.5% Greyhound, 16.3% American Staffordshire Terrier, 16.3% Rottweiler and 16.3% unknown mixed breed. Though he possesses a few traits of each breed, he definitely took on more of the German Shepherd look. His mom, Sharkie, is only 40 pounds but if we had to guess we would say he will be more likely 60+ pounds when full grown. He loves playing with his brothers and sisters and even enjoys wrestling with the resident kitty in his foster home every now and then. Meal time and cuddle time are a couple of his favorite times of the day. He is working hard on housebreaking and would love a family who would help him continue on with his training. Mako is an absolute joy who would make a great addition to any home…. could that home be with you?

Born 8/19/18 to mom Sharkie.  Petfinder requires a breed mix, but these pups are only mixed breed pups, not only the breeds listed.  DNA showed 6+ mixed breeds.

Please visit www.handsheartspaws.org for an adoption application

All of our dogs are current on vaccinations, spayed/neutered, microchipped, fecal tested, heartworm tested, and they are all on heartworm and flea/tick preventative.

The adoption process is an application, a vet reference, a home visit, and a lifetime contract. The requested adoption donation for this dog is $275___.

We do not REQUIRE a fenced in yard, we do REQUIRE a means of safe outside containment.  We do NOT adopt to homes that use invisible fencing.  Invisible fencing is NOT a safe means of outside containment.

We are willing to adopt out-of-state, contingent on our ability to complete a home visit, but you must travel to Omaha to complete the adoption. We do not transport or ship our dogs.

animal.description:
Pedey has been with the rescue for a long time now. He is a fear nipper and we have done everything we can  to work with him.  We have had a trainer here and he has come a long way,  but is still fearful of strangers. I feel the rescue has done everything we can  and it is t ime to help him find the perfect home. He needs a home without a ton of new people coming and going. He will love his person/people with all of his heart, but new people have to be either introduced slowly and with him on a leash, or he needs to do into another room while company is there. He is difficult to catch when he is excited,  like when someone new comes in. He will run from you and do circles. He will never be good with strangers. He will mark your furniture when upset. 

 He is the sweetest most cuddly dog you will ever meet after he gets to know you. He loves kisses and playing fetch. He is housebroken and crate trained and likes playing with the other dogs in his foster home.  

I know this will have to be the perfect match and his new person will have to be a very experienced dog handler. If not, he will end up biting someone and we don't want that to happen.

Pedey is up to date on vax and neutered. He is about 10 years old and 18 pounds. His adoption fee is 250.00. If you think you have his dream home, please complete an application. A completed and processed application are the first steps in the adoption process.

animal.description: So happy we were able to save Bo .  As of this morning he had no chance but we were able to find a foster at the last minute.  This is a very special breed and not common here in Florida. They are not for everyone and certainly not if you live in a condo. Needs a home and some land. He is a Treeing Walker Coonhound. He was a stray and went unclaimed. He was stressed in the kennel and needed to get out. His weight is 42LBS. Good health and a great heart!! He is fine with other dogs, just like to sniff around and around. What a nose!!!!!!! He is now in foster care in the country and that is great for him. He loves it!! He loves to ride on the tractor and loves to go after everything who is moving!! He is a great boy...  If you are worry about rats he will take care of them. Great hunting dog. We know that dogs in shelter are very stressed and only a few of them actually make it to adoption. Bo was tested and had no issues in the beginning. just needs a hand. Very handsome dog!! if you would like to meet him and adopt him please fill out the application online at www.findahomegiveahome.com  His adoption fee is $200.  His adoption fee will go toward training.

animal.description:
Logan was adopted pretty quickly when he was here before because he is such a good boy! BUT ... he is back again .... but it isn't his fault. For some reason, sometimes, Logan has seizures .... :-( His (now previous) owner's couldn't find any triggers or pattern to the few they witnessed and their vet didn't want to put him on medicine since he doesn't have them often. His owners have had 2 human babies since adoption Logan and the fear of such a giant dog flailing around and them in the middle of it is just too much. So, we are consulting with our homeopathic vet to address Logan's seizures. Adjustments are also being made to his diet to reduce his chances of another seizure. But if the right family was prepared to take on such a dog, he is a great and sweet boy that likes everyone - including other pets and children. He is obedient and happy. Please email for a questionnaire if you are interested in Logan. Pictures coming soon! Logan is 2 1/2 years old and black with a little white on his chest and some toes. He has uncropped ears and an average stature. ****************************************************************************************************** Details later - just wanting to get the new ones in the system!!

 

 

Please e-mail Charity for a questionnaire at shebangsrescue@yahoo.com 

We are a very busy pet health retail store so e-mail is easier for us to communicate with you!

animal.description:
Shelby's prior medical costs: $2,068.58

Shelby's medical costs 1-8-21 to 1-11-21: $1,323.12 (includes private cremation)

Please consider helping with the extraordinary costs involved with Shelby's care.

1-11-21: Once hospitalized, Shelby began to deteriorate during the day. We had committed up to $1,500.00 for her emergency care at our vet. It was clear she would need supplemental oxygen overnight at an emergency clinic. In contacting three different ER clinics, we were astounded at the costs for overnight oxygen at $1,300.00 - $3,000.00. During the late afternoon, we spent almost 3 hours with Shelby, continuing to hope that her oxygen levels would rise. By 5.00 pm, her levels were maintaining at only 64%. We were helping with the administration of direct oxygen through a nasal tube. Our vets were amazing with suggestions and stayed long past closing time to help Shelby. But in the end, at 6.40 pm, Shelby, on her own terms, left us to travel to the Rainbow Bridge. This sweet angel is now running free. We are heartbroken at the loss.

1-11-21: Shelby is hospitalized with low oxygen levels (under 80%). She is currently being given oxygen and may need to be transferred to an overnight emergency clinic so she can continue to have oxygen administered to her.

1-9-21: Shelby returned to the vet this morning to check her oxygen levels. She is refusing food. Shelby has returned to her foster home to be carefully monitored in case she needs to be transferred to an emergency clinic over the weekend.

1-8-21: A day full of tests for Shelby... Bloodwork, complete abdominal ultrasound, urinalysis, and x-rays. After being on oxygen for several hours, our vets began these tests to determine what is causing Shelby's breathing issues. All test results were sent to a Pathologist who then determined no cancer has been found in her organs or lungs. She does have some fluid in her lungs, which is now being treated with antibiotics. The doctors, as well as us, are all "stumped" as to what is causing Shelby's problems. She is now back at her foster home and will be closely watched over the weekend.

1-7-21: Today, for yet unknown reasons, Shelby began having difficulty breathing and was rushed to our vet. X-rays show some irregular areas in her lungs, but all of her blood tests have normal results. We are nervously waiting for the results of an in-depth abdominal ultrasound.

11-2-20: Shelby's urine culture results have come in and she is now resistant to Doxycycline and a Sulpha drug that we have used in the past. A new Rx has been called into our pharmacy, which we will pick up tomorrow and start her newest treatment. It's worrisome that she is having to take so many different antibiotics to clear the UTI.

10-28-20: Yet again, we are battling another UTI with Shelby. 2 weeks of Doxycycline did not help this time. We've now sent out a sterile sample to be cultured ($165 each time), which will let us know which specific medication will "kill" her current infection. She is back at her foster home tonight, after being at the vet all day. The sweetheart has been sleeping all evening.

9-2-20: We have been treating Shelby with a specific antibiotic after a urine culture determined which medication would stop her constant urinary infections. While we believe her UTI's are resolved, they may continue to occur, resulting in accidents.

5-12-20 Shelby is at the vet today. We are attempting to determine why she is having recurring UTI's. We'll post more information after test results are received.

Shelby should be adopted by a family that has the time, patience and experience to care for a blind dog. She startles easily and should not be around small children.

-------------------------------------------------------------

UPDATE: 10-8-18 Shelby was groomed and looks and feels FANTASTIC! She has almost completely recovered from her 11 dental extractions and we are now slowly increasing her food mix from all soft food to both wet & dry. She remains on antibiotic medications.

Shelby came to us when her human could no longer care for her. Shelby is an adorably sweet Scottie who lost her sight some time ago. Shelby is completely blind.

Our first priority was taking her to our vet for a complete physical, blood tests, fecal and urinalysis, in addition to testing for heartworms, Ehrlichia , Anaplasmosis and Lyme disease. Shelby needed a dental in the worst way, which was done the following morning. Sadly, she lost 11 teeth to decay.

In just 48 hours, we have already expended over $750.00 for this precious girl and are asking for help with her medical costs. A donation button is located on our website: www.scottiekingdom.com

or

Donations may be made via PayPal to email address:

Donate@scottiekingdom.com

or via USPS, to PO Box 551265 ~ Dallas, TX 75355

- - - - - - - - - - - - -

All dogs adopted by Scottie Kingdom Rescue, Inc. have had a full medical exam by one of our licensed Veterinarians, which includes testing (and treatment, if necessary) for Heartworm disease, Lyme disease, Ehrlichia and Anaplasmosis, all necessary vaccinations, spay/neuter surgery, dental cleaning as necessary, microchipping, registration of the microchip, and any other medical needs each particular dog may need. Copies of all available medical records are transferred to you when the adoption is finalized.

We prefer to adopt to families with past Scottie, Westie, Terrier experience, but realize this isn't always possible. We do NOT ship our pets. If you have that special place in your heart, and in your home, for a Scottie (or any of our other available rescue dogs), please visit us in Dallas for an in person meet & greet session with our available dogs. If you have existing dogs, they should travel to Dallas with you, so we can be assured that they will be compatible with the new addition to your family.

Please contact us at
Rescue@scottiekingdom.com
to receive an Adoption Application or for more information on our Adoption process. Also, please take the time to visit our website
www.scottiekingdom.com
for additional information.

We sometimes receive several applications on the same dog. Our goal is to place the dog in the best home possible, based on his/her needs, personality and past history. Please note: Adoptions are not done on a first come, first served basis. Submitting an application does not guarantee the adoption of any dog. We are looking for the best available home for each of our rescue dogs.

Thank you for your understanding, and for considering adoption!

We are
not
supported by your tax dollars or public grants, rather, we rely on donations to help us continue our rescue work for animals that are in need.

Donations may be made via PayPal to email address:

Donate@scottiekingdom.com

All dogs adopted through Troy Animal Rescue Project are up to date on vaccinations, spayed/neutered (age appropriate), and heartworm negative. All dogs are given monthly flea/tick preventative, monthly heartworm preventative, and are dewormed regularly. Dogs adopted through Troy Animal Rescue Project are microchipped. Adoption fee is $50. Home visit and vet reference required. Applications can be put in online at http://www.troyanimalrescueproject.org/adopt.php or in person at our rescue center.

The address for our rescue center is 34 County Road 2266, Brundidge, AL 36010. We are one turn off Hwy 167. If you use Google maps, type in Troy Animal Rescue Project and it will take you right to us. Hours of operation are from 10-3 daily. We are open Saturdays and Sundays. No appointment necessary for pets that are located at the rescue center. Appointments must be made to visit pets in foster homes. Appointments can be made by calling 334-508-2367 or emailing troyanimalrescueproject@gmail.com. Location information will be listed beside the pets name if they are at a location other than our rescue center.

Questions can be emailed to troyanimalrescueproject@gmail.com or call 334-508-2367.

animal.description:
Beautiful Girl Elle is a VERY sweet girl, and looking for that one family or person who she will make her everything.  She would do best either as Queen of the Castle OR with a Male dog or a younger dog/puppy (2 or under but should be male).  She does very well with younger dogs/puppies as she was a one time momma dog and still loves to play  She is used to being an indoor dog and being very loved.  She knows basic commands and has had basic training on lead, along with sit, down, giving paw, etc.

Elle is a beautiful very light brindle color with white markings. She is so sweet and loving - and listens very well, just wanting to please.  Need an Emotional Support Dog?  Elle is your girl!!  She's obedient and just loves to love. She can become protective of her family, so an experienced dog person is needed.  She is our longest member at the rescue, so she is truly deserving of her forever home NOW!

Elle just wants to enjoy her youth, she is pretty laid back for a Pittie, but every once in awhile likes to get her Ya-Ya's out. Elle would love be the love of someone's life.  She is spayed, up-to-date on vaccines, microchipped, and wormed, so a warm bed, food, and someone to love is all of her requirements. 

***SideNote: Elle has been tried in an Apartment Environment and was over-stimulated by the noises and lots of people and dogs - so she will need to be adopted out into a Single Family Home Environment Only****

NOTE: No Apartments will be considered for our large dog placements.  We also do NOT adopt out Out of State - adoptions are confined within a 2 hour drive from 92590 zip code

Please consider this gorgeous girl as she will provide tons of LOVE into your home.

home_environment_attributes.other_animals: Does not do well with horses - does well with younger dogs

animal.description: Trixie came to ARCC from a horrible situation. She was seized by local Law Enforcement after it was determined she was being a public nuisance. Trixie's previous owner housed her in a dilapidated shed where she had a litter of 8 puppies she was protecting. Trixie's strong instince of survival and protection of her puppies and her "home" caused her to chase anyone near and around her area. Trixie has come a long way. Her puppies were all adopted and we have worked with her to overcome her aggression. Trixie absolutely ADORES her people, but her people aren't her people until she gains your trust which takes time and patience. Trixie has a tendency to guard what is hers whether it's her space, her food, or her people. We are looking for a good home for our girl with an experienced dog owner, a big yard with a sturdy and contained fence and play yard because she loves to play and she LOVES the water. If you would be interested in meeting this awesome girl, please contact us at arcc.rescue@gmail.com

animal.special_needs_notes:
What a sweet guy.  Ollie always has a look on his face that never fails to draws you over and gets him lots of petting.  :)  Ollie was born around August 2015 and weighs 55 lbs.  He's friendly and calm and just wants someone to love him. Due to his size and preference to have all the attention on him he needs a home with adults only.

Ollie has heartworms but we will see him through this.  Heartworms aren't contagious, you and other animals will not contract heartworms from him.  They're curable when caught early and show no outward symptoms except in advanced cases (coughing).  Heartworms are caused by mosquitoes and are all too common here in the south but are completely preventable with an inexpensive monthly pill.  Ollie is taking a monthly pill (which we'll pay for) until a blood test (which we'll also pay for) shows he's rid of them.  This could take 6 months to over a year.  We've had many happy adopters who've rescued a heartworm-positive dog.  Speak to your vet if you need more feedback.

Email Homelesspetsfoundation@gmail.com or call 770-971-0100 for more info. To increase your odds of having first dibs on an animal, fill out an adoption application, found at www.homelesspets.com/adoption-form.

Adoption fees include spaying/neutering, micro-chipping, vaccinations up to date at the time of adoption, one free check-up at Town & Country main vet clinic within 14 days of adoption, a free session with Tenasity dog trainers and 6 months of Affordable Pet Care.

animal.description:
Noel

Breed: American Pit Bull Terrier, Boxer mix
Housetrained: Partially
Compatibility with other animals: Must be the only pet
Compatibility with children: Best in a home with no children or children visitors
Knows: Sit 
Preferred home environment: Securely fenced-in yard (six feet high or taller) required 
Intake date/origin: December 2017, found stray
Vetting: Already spayed, microchipped, and UTD on vaccines including rabies
Adoption fee: $150
Location: Shelter facility

Noel is a wonderful dog for the right person. Sweet and silly, she is desperately looking for somebody who will foster or adopt her and provide her with the guidance and direction she has never received. Having lived in the shelter system since December 2017, Noel has developed some habits that we believe could be more easily corrected if she was in a different environment. Even if you are not the person who is able to provide for Noel’s needs, please share her information far and wide in hopes that somebody else will step up and give her a chance.

Born in 2016, Noel arrived as an unclaimed stray one week before Christmas in 2017. Noel has blossomed into a sweet, loving, playful, and happy girl, having a knack at making her caregivers smile at her silly antics. She also seems to have a special talent for jumping very high, so she must have a tall, secure fence (six feet high or taller) to ensure she cannot escape if she sees something worth “investigating.” Although Noel did not appear to be housetrained when she was in a larger kennel, she does seem to “hold it” better when in a more confined crate. With a consistent schedule and boundaries, she may do well with housetraining when in a home.

Noel’s biggest issue is meeting new people. Some people she likes, but others she doesn’t like. We don’t know if her behavior has changed since living in the stressful shelter environment or if she was never properly socialized as a puppy, but anybody interested in fostering or adopting her will need to meet her several times. Additionally, any household where Noel goes (at least for the time being) should have few or no visitors. As far as other animals are concerned, Noel has shown aggression toward other female dogs. Although she previously had a male dog friend who she loved to play with, she must be the only pet unless otherwise determined. 

The longer Noel remains in the shelter environment, the harder we know it will be for her to find a home. Although we can wish all we want that the perfect person will come and adopt Noel, we know that it won’t happen unless Noel receives some training. Since she is still so young, we think her bad habits can be managed, if not trained out of her. Her behavior might also improve when out of the shelter environment. 

We may not be able to change the world for all dogs; but if we all work together, we can change the world for Noel. And one dog at a time, a difference can be made.

Will you help us help Noel?
