animal.description:
Please consider fostering an Alaskan Malamute for our rescue. You save the life of the dog that you foster for us, and also the life of the next dog that fills the space where our dog was. Our primary goal is to find fur-ever homes for as many Malamutes as possible.

If you are interested in adopting, please email MalRescueDE@gmail.com for an application.  Once your application is processed, a home visit is required.  There is an adoption fee of  $250 for each adult dog. Our dogs  are healthy, spayed or neutered, up to date on shots, and heartworm negative. 

Unfortunately rescues don't have the ability to hold dogs for adopters.  Dogs are adopted to approved adopters on a first come, first serve basis. Our goal is to get a dog adopted to a forever home so that we can then help another one. If you are interested in one of our dogs, the first step is to request an application, which is typically sent to you the same day you have emailed your request. We process your application the day it is received. The next step is a home visit, and then you will be invited to meet the dogs. While we represent the State of Delaware, AMROD’s dogs are fostered in  west-central  Virginia.  Contact  preference  is  by  email,  malrescuede@gmail.com,  rather  than  by  phone.  We  appreciate  you  considering  an  AMROD  dog!

home_environment_attributes.other_animals: Malamutes have same gender aggression and a high prey drive. They do not do well with small animals.

animal.description: Abbie is a unique dog.  As you can see, she is absolutely gorgeous! She has had some rough years, though.  We took her from the Orange County Shelter about four years ago where she was about to be killed for biting one of the shelter workers.  But we always have to give them a break when they are in such a scary place like a county shelter.  So Abbie came to live with us here at the rescue.  It turns out, she had some early onset arthritis, which may explain her tendency to lash out when she is touched in a sensitive area.  We are looking for a family for Abbie who will understand her limitations.  She does not like to be touched, and will always let us know when she has had enough on her walks. She would like a home with no children or other pets.  She will require a home with a special kind of person who will respect her space when she asks for it.  Abbie has lived in a kennel most of her life, so if you are a patient person who can give Abbie a home of her own, please come meet her1

animal.description: Meet Spike - He's a senior Fiest Mix that came to us from Pocohantus County. They say he is 19 years old but wow! Spike still has a lot of love to give and trusts quickly and seems to do great with all the dogs here and love attention of people too. He also learned his territory here very quickly with a little help and follows my voice when we need to go outside. He even finds his way into an open crate for a nap on an occasion. Spike is now up to date on his vaccines, heart worm and lymes negative, neutered and micro chipped. We also tested negative for glaucoma. He is ready and that was and looking for his new forever family. Emails us for an application at mmadoptions@gmail.com

animal.description:
Daisy was pulled from a high risk shelter and has been fostered by a wonderful family. She is around 4 yrs old, spayed, heartworm negative and on prevention. 

Daisy loves to go ride and will sit shotgun any chance she gets. She's absolutely house trained and holds it for a long time when necessary. She LOVES all people and is crate trained. In fact she lays in it often without being told. and when she needs to be in it, all I say is "crate" and point and she walks right in and plops right down. 

Daisy doesn't like all dogs but when she needs to be the only pet. While she loves to go for a walk and does well on a leash, she's also a lazy girl and is happy to just lay around in the same room as her people. She also LOVES toys and will toss it up and keep herself entertained for quite a while. She is a very charming girl with lots of cute and entertaining characteristics. She makes us laugh often with her silly antics. She weighs around 60 lbs, but as you can see she could stand to loose a bit (we love her though)!  Daisy has a high prey drive and will need a fenced in yard.  Due to her size lack of manners (jumping) she will need to go to a family with older children.  (10+)

Adoption fee is $175 and includes: spay/neuter, parvo/distemper series of shots, rabies (if dog is old enough), bordatella, heartworm preventative while here, worming, and microchip.

If you are interested in meeting and/or adopting one of our dogs, please visit our website and fill out an application: NorthMeckAnimalRescue.org

animal.description:
This adorable boy is Cash. Cash has been a longtime adoptable dog with us. He spent time with our trainer and some time in boarding until we could get him into one of our homes to be evaluated before getting him into his forever home. 

Cash is 6 years old and is a stubborn boy! When he wants something, he will let you know! When he doesn’t want to move, he won’t! But we are making progress! He listens very well and is highly treat-motivated. He just wants to have a comfortable life with lots of attention.

Cash should be an only dog with no children, a single person would be best. With Cash, you must establish and maintain your dominance or he will know and start to test you. A single owner would probably be best so he knows you are in control. 

He has claimed the chair as “his” and 99% of the time, I will find him chilling on it. He is not high energy at all. We will require an experienced adopter since he is so stubborn so if you love his sweet face, send us an email and we can chat about Cash. 

Let’s get this handsome devil into his forever home soon!

animal.description:
Betty is a young adult lab-boxer mix who was neglected and was picked up as a stray. She used to get along well with other dogs in her old neighborhood, but has been at the Rescue a long time and is now very aggressive to other dogs. She adores people, especially children. She was adopted for a few weeks and used to put the children to bed and make sure they were tucked in.

She walks great on a leash, but other dogs must be avoided. She has had such a sad life, but is still a cheerful dog and would make a great companion in a home where no other dogs visit, with a secure fenced yard. UPDATE: Betty has a Guardian Angel who has sponsored her adoption fee in hopes it would encourage a nice person to take a second look at Betty. She is also in foster care as of 01/02/2021. 

All our dogs are spayed/neutered, de-wormed, vaccinated appropriate for their age, vaccinated for kennel cough, and micro-chipped. Puppies (under 6 months) are $225.00; puppies (6 months to 1 year) are $175.00, dogs (over 1 year) are $150 and senior dogs (7 years or older) are $60.00.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Please contact Lynn & Cedric (lynnwelcomesyouhome@gmail.com) for more information about this pet. All of our dogs and cats are in foster homes and we have no paid staff. If you have questions concerning a specific animal, PLEASE fill out an application and the foster parent will be in touch. We will not arrange any home visits with any of our dogs and cats until your application is processed. Please understand our foster parents are precious to our 2nd Chance family; without them we cannot function, so we do our best to not burden them with multiple appointments. Our foster parents will choose their top 3 applications and arrange home visits with these applicants. The adopter will be chosen at that time. The process can take anywhere from a week to a month. We want to make sure our little furry ones are placed in their 'forever home' and never have to go through a rehoming again!Meet Sugar :) She is an absolutely beautiful little girl who got dumped in a kill shelter when her owner died. She was rescued shaking and cowering in the corner of her cage in the big scary shelter. She is proving to be a wonderful companion in her foster home and wiggles her whole rear end when spoken to and rolls over for belly rubs. She is medium to low energy, preferring to just sit with the humans and be petted or follow you around on your chores. She is also up for a game of fetch now and then and loves to chew on nyla bones. Sugar tends to try to be queen of the castle and would do best as an only dog or with a larger dog (25lbs and over) who would not put up with her bossiness. She will play with other freindly dogs. She is spayed and microchipped and has had all her vaccinations. Fill out an application now if you think Sugar would be a good fit in your home. She is a wonderful little lady and deserves a great forever home!Please fill out an adoption application:
Adoption application (Dog)
Adoption Application (Cat)

Please understand we do not adopt out dogs to
families with children under the age of 5. We do not adopt dogs to renters. Some dogs will have fence requirements while others may not.

A pet is a lifetime commitment. The dogs and cats in our system find themselves there, for the most part, because their humans did not have the same loyalty to them as they did to their owners. We do not take the adoption process lightly, and will do everything in our power to make sure the animal is placed correctly the first time around for your sake and theirs. Thank you for choosing to adopt not shop!

animal.description:
Pacino is a young male bully mix - about 2 years old & medium build.  He is fully vaccinated and neutered, and has no health concerns with the exception of issues with ear infections.

Pacino had a rough start in life & takes significant time to warm up to new people, if he is willing to engage, as he displays visible fear of new surroundings.  Pacino becomes afraid around other dogs & would prefer to be the only pet in his forever home to ensure he can consistently do as well as possible. In his home, he allows all handling from his foster mom & will sometimes open up periodically to new people before becoming afraid & unsure.  Pacino has learned commands & general training in his foster home & loves receiving his treats when he does well.  He loves to run & play outside & chews his toys with no issues as long as he feels safe.  He is also crate trained & sleeps in there each night.  Ideally, he is seeking a place with someone experienced with difficult &/or abused dogs/breeds & is equipped with the time, space & resources to work him through struggles. A trainer, animal health professional, behaviorist, someone involved in rehabilitation, etc. is Pacino's best chance at a successful & safe adoption, & he is waiting for that person to find him here.

Pacino is available for adoption through Pit of Our Souls Rescue!

animal.description:
This beauty is Barkley, and we are hoping that the perfect forever home is out there for this sweet girl. She is a special gal who has a few quirks, but lets face it...dont we all?! Barkley is 4 years old, and we are told is a lab/boxer mix, but its possible she may have some pit in her as well. She does well with all dogs that are around her size or larger. She hasnt lived with cats, but she has been a little too interested in the cats she has come into contact with...so we are recommending a cat-free home. Barkleys ideal home would be a calm household on a quiet street with minimal visitors and a fenced-in yard. She tends to get nervous when meeting new people, and her forever family will need to understand that shell need some time and a safe space (her crate) to allow her to warm up and be more comfortable. Once she is bonded with her people she also tends to be a bit protective of them, so may need to be crated if new people visit her home. Barkleys foster mom says once she is comfortable with people, she is so very sweet, goofy, cuddly, and lovable! She loves bones, playing ball, and her stuffed toys. She is crate-trained, keeps a very clean kennel, and is fully house-trained. She also loves playing and snuggling with her 4-legged foster siblings, so Barkley would love another dog in her forever home to both learn from and bond with. She also loves going for walks, but does need consistency and continued training when on-leash as she does get stressed and vocal when meeting other dogs/people when leashed. Having some yummy treats along on her walks definitely helps! She will need an experienced owner with an abundance of patience and grace. We are also recommending no young children in the home (kids ages 15+ would be best). We know that her perfect home is out there...and we would appreciate you sharing her gorgeous face so that we can all help Barkley find her forever! 

**If you have any questions about Barkley, please feel free to reach out to us! Her adoption fee includes her spay, vaccines, heartworm test, and microchip.

animal.description:
Note: Dogs are pack animals and do not do well away from other members of their pack. The adopter is the alpha member of the pack, and the dog or puppy needs as much one-on-one contact with the alpha as possible. For this reason, all Route 66 Rescue Inc. dogs are adopted to inside homes only. They must be on leash, or inside a secure fence when outside, and not left outside alone when no one is home. Invisible fencing does not qualify as protection since other animals and strangers have access to the dog. The dogs must be returned to Route 66 Rescue, Inc. if ever given up by the adopter. Thank you for understanding we want only the best for the dogs you give a forever home.

Kipp is a sweet, quiet, but just a tad nervous with new people kind of boy.  He needs some reassurance and time to adjust but will be a great addition to a settled, gentle adult home.  He is pretty much a one-person fellow, so a single adult would be the best situation for him.  He will be totally devoted to his person.  Kipp's birthday is 8/09/2015, and on 2/05/.2020 he weighed 24.5 pounds.  His adoption fee is $200.

To request an adoption application, please email info@route66rescueinc.org . Thank you for visiting our site. Please come back often.

animal.description:
*** Due to COVID 19, we are cautious for the safety of our Foster Homes and Adopters with human to human contact. We need to safely do home visits, meet and greet, and Adoptions. Please be patient as we can do the Pre-Checks but may need more time to complete the Adoption process.

8/20/20- Gunner had his Annual exam, shots, and ProHeart 6 for 6 months heartworm prevention. Vet wants him to not get over 60 lbs..He is doing great and bloodwork is excellent. He just needs his Forever Home!

GUNNER- Happy 5th Birthday Gunner (estimated dob 8/16/15) We rescued him 2 years ago. He came to us heartworm positive with an old injury of a broken hip. He went through heartworm treatment, had xrays, and exam with Orthopedic Vet. He does have separation anxiety and doesn't like to be alone. He has to be crated in a secure plastic crate when you are not home.  He has had several homes in his life and we want the best for him. We love Gunner and we have not found the right Forever Home. Please read all about him. 

He is a total sweetheart!! Everyone who meets him loves him. He is full of love, nosey like a Boxer, and a STRONG high energy Boxer, who wants all of your attention. He is very social and loves playing and going for walks with his Foster Dad. He needs a home where his family is not gone a lot. He loves his Foster Mom who works from home. He would rather be doing something and not just laying on the couch. He will snuggle with his humans and other dogs, cats and older kids when resting. He has to have another dog in his home. He is great with other medium to large dogs that are not dominant, as he wants to be the leader of the pack. He doesn't like small dogs. He will plow through all the dogs to get to his Foster family so not good if you have a jealous dog. He is good with cats in his Foster Home. He lets them lay next to him and rub against him. He will chase them if they are running and think he just wants to play. Kids need to be 10 yrs and older and experienced with large dogs, as he doesn't know his size and strength. He gets so excited and will jump up on kids and adults just for love. Best with a Boxer experienced family. He needs an active family that has the time and is going to do things with him. He has been many times to PetsMart for training and very smart, just needs Adopter to be in charge. BTW he is a big strong drooler/slobberer with those jowls, so have a towel ready! 

Gunner can walk, run, jump, jump up on things, and gets around great! He has a few restrictions with his old injury of broken hip most likely causing from being hit by a car. He is on daily Rimadyl and this summer with the heat/humidity his hip has been bothering him. He has needed more Rimadyl and not able to go on his daily walks which he loves. He also takes Glucosamine  Adopter needs to be able to watch for signs that he is having issues and adjust meds and exercise. His Vet and Orthopedic Vet have recommended no surgery. He has to get exercise to keep his back right hip muscles in good shape. He needs to maintain his current weight and not gain weight to put more pressure on his hips/back. 

Adoption fee at 5 years old is $225. He is neutered, shots, rabies, microchipped, fecal/heartworm negative and on heartworm prevention. At least a 6 ft+ privacy fenced in yard is required for Gunner. He is to be an indoor dog. Go to www.BoxerRescueOfTexarkana.com to How to Adopt for our Requirements and online Adoption Application. 

We adopt in AR, TX, LA and OK in areas where we have support. Please let us know if you are out of this area to see if we could consider your area.

Monty has been with us for 2 years now.

Not because he doesn't deserve a family or is incapable of loving, but because he is too protective.

Monty has shown tremendous love to his caretakers over the past 2 years but is reactive with new people so showing him for adoptions has not gone too well,

Knowing the fantastic dog that he is we are determined to find the right placement for him. 

Some things that Monty enjoys are nice long walks at the forest preserve, trips to Menards and Petsmart, fast food drive through treats, playing with other dogs, playing on the trampoline and cuddling.

We know that it will take someone with EXTREME experience and tolerance with stubborn pups to get him settled and on the right track in a new home so we have to remain hopeful that he will catch the eye of someone that fits that description.

It wont be an easy road to start but if given an opportunity to show his great side we are confident he will shine.

If you are interested in Monty please submit an adoption application on our website www.perfectpawsanimalrescue.org.

animal.description:
We rescued Rover from the local shelter....his short-stack stature and wiggly body as he happily wagged his tail caught our attention! 
We believe ROVER is a mix of pit bull and Bassett hound, but without DNA testing we can’t be sure if his breed. He is about 2.5 yrs old and weighs approx 85 lbs. He is a ‘low rider’ ... a massive body on short stout legs! 
Rover is a fun loving, happy and playful pup! He has a very sweet disposition and wants to please you. 
He loves to run and play fetch as well as cuddle in your lap. He is a great hugger too! 
Rover is crate trained and housetrained. He still has a lot of 'puppyness' to him though, so you will need to stay on top of his antics! 
He likes to play with his kong toys and will keep busy chewing on Benebones. His foster Mom is working on his leash skills, and he is getting better but will need ongoing leash work.. He is a very strong boy! 
Rover would do best with an interactive family that will include him in activities and have him be a real part of the family. He is a large, solid dog that is a bit clumsy, and can be a 'bull in the china closet' so he could knock over young children and/or toddlers accidentally...for this reason he is only available to homes with no young children. (under 12 yrs of age)
He loves to play with doggie friends but should be in a home with NO OTHER DOGS OR CATS. He has a very rough play style so small dogs can easily get hurt and big dogs need to be submissive, passive and able to handle rough play due to his size and strength. 
Rover is a big squishy love bug that will be a great family dog for an experienced bully breed owner.
He has puppy playful energy so he will need daily exercise or will get bored and develop bad habits.....his clumsy antics will keep you smiling! He has a big heart and lots of love to give.

**HOME OWNERSHIP AND BULLY BREED EXPERIENCE IS REQUIRED TO ADOPT THIS DOG**

ADOPTION FEE IS $300 which includes health exam, spay, current vaccinations, micro chip, flea and worming treatment, along with any other medical or dental deemed necessary by our veterinarian.

home_environment_attributes.other_animals: No horses, livestock, chickens, rabbits, gerbils, or other farm animals

animal.description:
Gary was brought in as a stray and wasnt claimed by an owner.  He is about 4 years old and he loves treats.  Gary can be both friendly and affectionate, and yet sometime unfocused and disinterested in what the human end of the leash is asking him to do.  He pulls on leash, he jumps up, he can be gently mouthy but he does know how to sit on cue.  He is a big dork and he probably has had very little structure and expectations placed on him.  He doesn't have a great respect of boundaries, but he means no harm.  He will bark at us for attention when he is in his kennel, but when taken outside, just wants to go where he wants to go.  He met a very playful and friendly female dog and did very well with her.  He presents as a bit of a challenge due to his "pulling has always worked for me" behavior, but can definitely learn in the right environment.  We also believe we will see a nice change in focus and behavior once he is neutered!

Gary's adoption fee is $150 and includes neuter, current vaccines, microchip, free vet visit, 30 days free pet health insurance, and custom engraved ID tag.

animal.description:
Hendrick is a sweet boy at 70lbs, white with a super funny long tongue. He is super friendly with people, is good on long walks, playing ball, and is a couch potato. He is not a big runner and is laid back, but playful. Hendrick is house trained and crate/kennel trained.

Hendrick's back story is that he was found tied to a fire hydrant after being used as a bait dog, which is one reason intact dogs with testosterone are a big issue for him.  He is a lucky dog to have been taken in by a local vet office who has loved him back into good health.

Hendrick needs an experienced dog owner who will give him exercise, structure, and consistency and be willing to work with him. He is a quick learner, food motivated and quite smart. He would do great as an only pet. He is a very sweet, strong happy boy who would be happy just sitting next to you on the sofa. 

Hendrick really wants a forever loving home who will give him the love and security he so deserves. If you would like to meet Hendrick  or know more about this wonderful boy, please send us an email at SittingPrettyPetBoarding@gmail.com

This dog is not available to an out of the area adoption because of difficulty to follow up. If you do not live within a 30-minute drive of Torrance, please do not apply. 
Please note that we are all volunteers, so it may take up to 3 days to process your application, but you will hear back from us. 
We do not have a shelter so individual appointments must be made to meet the pet you are interested in. Our pets are fostered/boarded in Torrance, CA 90501.

animal.description: Here is JESSE, a beautiful, earnest dog who is longing for love and attention that he deserves.  He is full of energy but not insanely wound up, he longs and craves to play with people and (some) other dogs. He would enjoy being the only dog in a house, but he would probably get along fine with another female who had a laid-back temperament. He likes to jog with his foster dad and would be a great running buddy.He enjoys playing fetch and  is also great at cuddling on the sofa.  He loves to sit in your lap, gives hugs and kisses.”

More about him from his foster: He is Moderately active, Leash trained, Crate trained, Does well in a car, Likes toys, Playful, Affectionate, obedient and goofy. Best with Older/considerate kids. Not a fan of kitties

Meet Marcel
Marcel had spent his time as a puppy chained in the backyard.  He was found by a Streetdog Volunteer who dutifully contacted owner information on his tags and returned him.  Less than 1 week later, he was found over 7 miles away from his home by someone else, exhausted and hungry.  This time, his owners did not return any calls about their found dog.  So now Marcel is officially a Streetdog and loving every minute of it.  

Marcel prefers dogs that are smaller than him and needs a day or so to warm up to new pup friends. He would prefer a home with older children because of his large size.

*Behaviors not listed have yet to be tested.

animal.description:
Barbarossa came to his foster mama with his dog mom and brothers.  The brothers have both been adopted, but Barbarossa is still looking for his fur-ever home.  He is young, about a year old, and even though he weighs about 50 pounds, he is characterized as large due to his height.  Before being rescued Barbarossa had no experience being around people, and he is still very shy.  He is curious and learns quickly, but he needs constant reassurance and direction from his foster mama.  He will need a special human who has lots of time and patience to spend with Barbarossa and who also knows how to be a confident pack leader.  His foster mama feels that he would do better in an adult-only household.  Barbarossa is safe around children, but their quick, sudden movements scare him, and he runs and hides from them.  Barbarossa is crate-trained and learns quickly, but he does need practice with walking on a leash without pulling and other doggie manners.  He has the potential to be a wonderful addition to a home.  He just needs the patience and understanding of a special human who is willing to spend the time building trust with him.

Email: shortylittle@comcast.net  
Phone number 717 645 2511

Please contact me through text or email during the day. Calls are accepted between 6pm-9pm EST. Much thanks, Tammy Little

home_environment_attributes.other_animals: Barbarossa lives on a farm with his foster mom.  He is okay with other dogs but is highly interested in chasing the cats, goats, and other animals that live on the farm.

animal.description:
Meet Lil' Bit.  This shy, 5 year old, 50 pound mama came to her foster mama with her puppies about a year ago.  It became obvious very quickly that Lil' Bit had not spent much time around people before she was rescued.  Unlike other dogs that rush over to you and beg for attention, Lil' Bit is hesitant.  She will wait and watch you first, and then she will come over to sniff you.  Do not let this count her out as a dog-candidate for your family.  She is friendly, sweet, and wants affection.  It just takes her a little time to warm up to strangers.  Her foster mama feels that she would do better in an adult-only household.  Lil' Bit is safe around children, but their quick, sudden movements scare Lil' Bit, and she runs and hides from them.  Lil' Bit is good on a leash and is crate-trained.  She has the potential to be a wonderful addition to a home.  She just needs the patience and understanding of a special human who is willing to spend the time building trust with her.

Email: shortylittle@comcast.net  
Phone number 717 645 2511

Please contact me through text or email during the day. Calls are accepted between 6pm-9pm EST. Much thanks, Tammy Little

home_environment_attributes.other_animals: Lil' Bit lives on a farm with her foster mama and many other animals, such as dogs, cats, goats, chickens, and horses.  She is highly interested in the cats and other farm animals.  She will chase them.  She does, however, get along with most dogs.

animal.description:
Everyone loves Archer! This guy is the poster child for happiness. He always has a big bully smile on his face. Nothing gets him down (well, maybe being told "no"). He loves playing tug with you or another pup or running and walking in his wheelchair. All you have to do is say, "do you want to..." and he is at the gate waiting to be leashed up. 

Noah's Arks Rescue is all about giving an Abused Animal a second chance at life and to experience what true love is. We take animals that have been tortured, abused, and neglected and supply the emergency medical care required to get them well. We then provide rehab physically and mentally to prepare them for their new home and new life. We are located in Ridgeland, SC., and are by appointment only. All of our dogs are at our Rehabilitation Center either in hospice care or being loved on by staff until we find them forever homes. Please call 843.540.6755 or email NoahsArksRescues@mac.com with any questions. If you are interested, please fill out our Adoption Application at https://www.noahs-arks.net/nar-application. We do adopt out of state and will arrange transports. Our dogs are not allowed to fly cargo at any time.

animal.description:
Meet Buddy, a four-year-old and 120-pound puppy! He has had a few different homes and is looking for an experienced dog owner with large dog experience. 

Buddy can be a big goofball and he has a heart of gold. He knows many tricks that he is happy to show off, including resisting yummy treats until you tell him he can eat it! He uses his big voice to say "Hello" to new people and is very protective of his people. Buddy will need a patient person who understands he needs to be introduced to new people slowly and with positive reinforcement. He is picky about who he likes so a potential adopter will need to bring the whole family to meet him and should be prepared to do multiple visits as going really slow with introductions is very important for him and for you. Buddy does not like kids and will need an adult-only home without cats.

Buddy has separation anxiety and can be destructive when left alone so he would prefer a family where someone is around most of the time. When left alone he will need to be crated until he gets used to a new routine and may still need to be crated after this. 

Buddy is not a dog that can be off-leash. He is reactive to new people, kids, wildlife, and barking dogs, so for his safety, he needs to either be on a leash or in a tall fenced yard. He is energetic and will need someone who can play with him and burn some of his energy off each day. Buddy needs someone who lives in a single-family residence without cats and has enough room out back to exercise him. Buddy has been improving on his socialization but may never get to a point where he can walk in public. He is not a dog for someone who wants to bring him around town, to social gatherings, or on public hiking trails. 

When it comes to other dogs, with a proper introduction, he loves to play and wrestle. He is best friends with Jayne (who is also his mother and needs a home too) and has been able to play with some of the other shelter dogs. Buddy will need to meet any dogs in the household before adoption though to make sure both dogs get along.

If you are interested in adopting this charming boy, please start by filling out an adoption application that can be found on our website at trilakeshumanesociety.org or give us a call at 518-891-0017 if you would like a hard copy mailed to you. Once we have an approved adoption application we can set up an appointment for you to come in and meet Buddy, spend some time with him, and see if he is a good fit for you and your household.

animal.description: You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Richie and Lucille come to rescue from S. Carolina. Richie and Lucille were born in April 2018, probably siblings and definitely bonded. so at this time we are asking that they be adopted together. They came into rescue with demodex mange, and after treatment, they are doing great in their foster home, but they would really love a home to call their very own. They are crate trained and house-trained. They have suffered so much neglect in their lives already and as a result are very shy and timid in new situations. They are completely comfortable in their foster home now with the family that they know but new people can be a little scary for them still. Who can blame them after all they have been through?! We need to find a perfect forever home for them filled with patience and understanding while this amazing pair learns that not all humans are bad. Richie is the brown dog, and Lucille is the black dog. If you are interested in adopting Richie and Lucille, please put your application in here: http://www.rescuedogsrocknyc.org

animal.description:
Lola
Breed: Pit Bull
Gender: Female
Age: 1 year old
Size: Medium
Where you can find me: At WAG

 

Energy Level: Medium
Training Goals: To work one on one with her & a trainer to help overcome fears & anxieties
House trained? Yes
Kids? No
Cats? No
Dogs? No
Medical Needs: I have had a very unstable past, to help me cope with my fears I am on anti-anxiety medication!

About Me:
Hi, I'm Lola!

I am a very special girl who is looking for an experienced dog owner who I can love forever.  I need someone who is willing to work with a trainer and myself to work on getting over some of my fears. I have an unstable past and staff believe I was abused and neglected. When I meet new people my first instinct is to lunge and bark as I am quite fearful. Once I get to know and trust you I want nothing more than to sit on your lap - I am the biggest cuddle bug! 

When I first came to WAG, staff believe I didn't have much experience going for walks as I was mostly tied up in a yard. I would lunge and bark at every car and person I saw. Staff have been doing lots of training with me, and now I am only lunging when I see really scary vehicles like buses and trucks! I love going on walks in quiet areas, and my favourite thing is playing in water! I love streams, lakes, rivers and pools! I could splash around all day if you let me!

Although I do love a good walk, I can also be a huge cuddly couch potato, movies and snacks anyone? I'm your girl! I would be quite content running around a big yard and then snuggling the rest of the day away on a comfy couch! 

 I am quite fearful of men so I’d prefer to go to a home with a rad chick, or maybe 2 rad chicks! I’m not opposed to meeting a man, it just might take a few hangouts until I learn to trust you. Staff are working on my training every day and I have already shown so much progress! 

I will thrive in a calm, nurturing environment with people that will pay attention to any signs of anxiety I may show. I would love to live in a quiet area  - an apartment in a busy city is not for me! My favourites place to be is sitting on your lap or right next to you, giving you lots of hugs! I really am a loving and goofy girl, and WAG staff know that whoever adopts me will have the most affectionate and fun companion!

I need a home that is committed to me and ready to give me a life with love and adventure for the rest of my years. I am looking for a home where I am the number 1 focus and where I am the only animal! I can't wait to find my forever home.

My Story:
I have had a very unstable start to my life. I was impounded by the RCMP when my previous caregivers were arrested. They never returned to pick me up and I was left at WAG. It is believed that I was abused and neglected in my previous home, hence my fearfulness and anxiety. I have never had a stable home life, or proper training, both of which I need in my next home. I am quite sad that I've found myself at a shelter but I have settled into the stable routine well and impressed the staff at how much I have grown in my time here! I can't wait for a family that will commit a lifetime of love to me.

home_environment_attributes.other_animals: Lola should be in a home where she is the only animal

animal.description:
Bronco
Husky
Male
9 year(s) old
60 lbs.
Blue eyes
Gray-White-Black fur coat
Possibly good with dogs and cats
Good with kids over 10 years old
Normal energy level

Bronco has been with Free Spirit for quite some time, long enough that he's become accustomed to and prefers the outdoors, sitting in the grass, walking down the road basically any outdoor activity and he is for it. Bronco loves to be around people, he just does not want to cuddle. He'll rub against you and let you stroke him every now and then. Bronco would do best with someone who's around most of the day. He thrives knowing people are around and even calls “woo hoo” when he sees a volunteer just to say hello! If you're someone who has a quiet household and is looking for a companion to sit on the porch with or help you in the garden, Bronco would be your faithful sidekick.

 
Special Training:
Free Spirit Siberian Rescue cannot make any guarantee regarding the outcome of any cat testing done. The owner assumes full responsibility for the dog’s behavior and, per the requirement of the adoption contract, will enroll the dog(s) in obedience classes to aid in the process.

 If interested in this adorable canine please begin the adoption process by filling out an adoption application. Visit us on our website at www.huskyrescue.org/adoption-process for adoption applications. 

IMPORTANT: You will receive a confirmation email from one of our coordinators once we have received your application. Do NOT attempt to submit multiple times. If you haven't received an email from us within 72 hours, please send an email to us at: freespiritsiberianrescue@gmail.com 

Check out our website for more photos of available dogs at www.huskyrescue.org Free Spirit Siberian Rescue a 501c3 All Breed Shelter . We are a no-kill, 501(c)(3), non-profit animal rescue. All donations made to Free Spirit Siberian Rescue are tax deductible. So you can't adopt or volunteer, but really want to help? MONETARY DONATIONS ARE GRATEFULLY ACCEPTED AND ALWAYS NEEDED to pay for vaccinations and spay/neuter surgeries for healthy rescued dogs, and for medical care for those with special veterinary needs. You can make a difference RIGHT NOW, by donating via PayPal! Just visit us on our website at http://www.huskyrescue.org/donations and your donation will go to work, right away helping homeless Siberians and Husky mixes! The dogs thank you, and we do, too!

animal.description:
WE ARE A HOLISTICALLY APPROACHED RESCUE, AND EXPECT ONLY HOLISTIC/INTEGRATIVE CARE for our dogs. If you take a different approach we will NOT be a match. If you are interested in learning about this integrative approach to care, feel free to call, but be prepared to hear the difference between conventional and holistic care.

We ONLY accept phone call enquiries, written enquiries, messages or emails, will not be responded to. You MUST call us prior to filling out an adoption application after reading the requirements for adoption. Tel: 508-533-8251  8am-8pm ONLY. We cannot adopt to homes with children under 13 years old and you must be able to provide a previous Vet reference of care of a previous dog in the potential adopters names under 3 years ago. If you have not owned a dog before we would not be able to move forward. Please only leave ONE message.
We believe in a more holistic approach for care of these small dogs, that can live into their 20's if cared for naturally. Therefore we insist on an integrative approach to vet care ongoing, so please make sure you learn about this approach before contacting us. Copy and paste this link to read and learn about integrative medicine, BEFORE contacting us. Thank you.
'https://www.huffpost.com/entry/discovering-integrative-v_b_599944/amp'

Maggie is 4 years old, 12lbs and a sweet, happy and super smart energetic Poodle. We are looking for a family that will exercise her on a daily basis. Maggie deserves a great family that will love her and in return she will love them to full capacity, with kisses and hugs. Maggie also has a GREAT nose and would be a fantastic scent dog, for competition or work related. Maggie would chase a cat to play with it, so it would not be a good match. Maggie would only do well with an equal size and high energy level dog, as she wants to play. She would be great as an only dogs as well.

Requirements for adoption:
Fenced in yard without exception (physical fence for running off leash, attended) No electric fences.
Someone who loves to walk.
Someone home some or all of the day (no home for lunch situations or dog walkers or daycare)
MUST be prepared to take an integrative approach to vet care and nutrition. (Holistic and conventional care combined and minimal vaccines)
Other same size dog, but NO cats
 
We prefer contact by phone for enquiries: Tel: 508-533-8251 read adoption directions below.
ALL of our dogs are in private foster homes in Massachusetts, you will meet the dog after completing an adoption application and we arrange a home visit and bring the dog with us.

We are in Massachusetts and only adopt to a 75 mile radius of Dover, MA.. 
All of our dogs are spayed or neutered, up to date on vaccines, dental cleanings if needed, Micro chipped and go home with their history folder, new harness, leash, collar and the food they are being fed.

Poodles need to go to a professional groomer every 6-8 weeks at a cost of about $65, so please factor that into the costs associated with dog ownership.  To apply to adopt one of our Poodles, go to our website,
http://toypoodlerescue.net Toy Poodle Rescue 
and fill out our Adoption Application.  If you require more information please call 508-533-8251 All calls and applications will receive a response. Please DO NOT call, email or message us to ask if they are available, if it does not say adopted they are available.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.HERO NEEDS A HERO! He has been in kennel free boarding for too long because his foster was no longer foster and his original rescuer is no longer rescuing. A forever foster (but even better - an adopter) with large-breed experience is Hero's dream! We supply food, crate and other necessary items for our fosters & cover vetting at our vets. Hero came to us from Riverside Shelter where he was on the euthanasia list for his age. They also noted he had trouble walking. We expected to pick up a weak old guy with hip issues, but instead we picked up a young-at-heart guy who thinks he's still a young Buck! :) He has spent several months with our trainer who was amazed at his energy level. The only way you can tell his age - his beautiful grey mask and worn, rough pads on his backside. :( Other than that, he has no idea he's a mature gentleman. We are not sure of his breed but Shepherd/Boxer/Pointer/Pitbull have all been guessed as possible mixes. He is a beautiful, shiny, dark-chocolate brindle. He does best with submissive dogs. We don't know how he is with cats. Because he is strong and can be a bit nervous in new situations, we recommend a home with no kids. Can you give an old guy the home or forever-foster he so deserves?
Email cause4sbpaws@gmail.com or apply now: http://www.causeforsbpaws.org/forms/form?formid=3251

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
Some dogs just pull at your heartstrings. Some dogs teach us what inner strength and courage are all about. Some dogs just want to play and stay in the moment, one sniff of fresh air, one listening to the sounds of people laughing, birds chirping, wind blowing. Martin just wants to enjoy his life. Saved by Rescue Ridge from a local, overcrowded, inner city shelter, Martin awaits your love and his forever home in a foster home. He loves people! Martin is very smart and alert. He enjoys
company
. He is dog-friendly with dogs who understand that, because he is visually impaired, he doesn't always understand social cues and is a bit clumsy. Martin is best in a home with older children because he probably can only see shadows. This impairment doesn't stop him from enjoying running around the play yard at his foster home or snuggling on the couch by your side. He is affectionate and very sweet. If you put a treat in front of his face, he will try his best to take it gently but does not always succeed. He can't help it. He tries. Martin is housebroken. He needs a fenced in yard and needs supervision in the yard because he will follow a scent and can escape. He is a wonderful boy, around 5 yrs. old.
Will
you take him home and show him that his life matters? Please apply to adopt Martin in central N. J. at Rescue Ridge at rescueridge.com and text 732 546 8805 to meet him. Here is Martin's video debut
https://youtu.be/GJOkvYeHdmM

George von Clooney is an adorable 7-8-month-old Shepherd mix.   In his foster home, George has transformed from an originally shy guy to a personable puppy who wags a friendly hello to both people and other dogs.  He delights in playtime and can hardly get enough but, once de-energized, he’s big into cuddle time.  Like every pup, George likes to chew on things and he will pull on the leash during walks, but his very experienced foster dad has the patience required to train this boy into a mannerly gentleman.  George barks only when it is warranted and is housebroken as long as he has access to the outside.  He would love another dog to play with in his forever home.  Let us know if you’re interested in meeting our Gorgeous George!

Westside dog biographies, availability and new photos are updated regularly on our website! So, check in and log on often! 

Westside thanks you for looking at our amazing dogs and for choosing to save an animal's life through rescue. 

Don't forget to visit your local animal shelter...the source of many of our dogs.

animal.description:
Hi!  My name is JoJo. My nickname is Joie and my foster mom says I am definitely worth several looks!!!  I was found on the streets, picked up by animal control, and eventually pulled into my foster home.  Upon arrival, my foster family thought I might have a vision issue.  An ophthalmologist diagnosed me with retinal dysplasia that they suspect I was born with.  I have some limited vision but it doesn't stop me from doing anything in my foster home!  I love my foster brother and sisters.  I do very well in the house and yard so much that it is hard for my foster mom to remember that sometimes I might have trouble seeing when it is dusk or dark.   My foster mom says that I am a sweet, sweet girl who deserves my very own family!  I am house trained and crate trained. I love my toys but also just like hanging out with everyone.  I am almost 3 years old, full grown, and weigh 55 lbs. Please don't pass up an opportunity to meet me!

To start the adoption process, email us at happilyeverafter4dogs@yahoo.com requesting an application. This does not commit you in any way, but helps us make the best match between people and our available dogs.

DOB:07/13/17
Adoption Fee: $180.00 (Includes microchip registration).

All of our dogs are required to be INSIDE PETS ONLY. Our adoption process includes an application, check of vet records, interview, neutral site meet & greet with the dog and your family, home visit, and 5 day sleepover.

animal.description:
www.facebook.com/MissBelle2018

Meet Miss Belle. She is 1 years young American Staffordshire Terrier/Rottweiler/Boxer cross whose interests include cuddling, jumping, exploring, running, romping and chewing. She loves having toys to play with, so her new home will need to provide her with her own toys, bones, playtime, and some training to keep her mind and body healthy. She loves water play and tug o war games. This sweet girl is almost leashed trained, has some basic commands down, she gets along well with people and most dogs. She likes to sleep with her human.

She has a mild prey drive and is curious about cats so she will need more practice with this. Belle likes to cuddle with you or lay down with you, wherever you may be or whatever you may be doing. She is a sweet and curious dog who wants to explore the world. She is young and willful which means she will need a strong leader.

Belle will be happiest when she can be a part of her person's daily activities. Her family will need to be sure that Belle feels like she is part of a close-knit group. She will need to be spayed, micro chipped, vaccinations complete, licensed in August and has a complete health workup. Miss Belle is still growing her fur on her body from the neglect she was rescued from and some physical scars may still remain from her abuse. Especially on her chin. Dr seems to think she will grow into some of her scars. We have found lamb, duck and salmon work well for her or many of the limited ingredient foods. She will go home with her new family with all her medical records and DNA test results.

Are you looking to add an energetic, beautiful, active, smart, loving girl to your family? What about a social companion ready for any adventure with you? Come see Miss Belle! She is available for adoption through the Miss Gabriel Foundation.

animal.description:
Hi! My name is Jasmine and I am looking for a family of my own to create memories with. I was hoping you would take some time to get to know me and see if we could be the perfect match! I am a shy and affectionate 2-year old American Staffordshire Terrier/Rottweiler mix. I have my basic commands down and I am eager to please. My favorite activities include tug-o-war, water games, and cuddling in bed. 

You might be wondering how I came to live with my foster family at the Miss Gabriel Foundation. It all started when I was just eight weeks old. My seven siblings and I were rescued from a hoarding situation in California and it was essential for us to find a place that could handle our various medical needs. We were all underweight and sick with bacterial infections and needed to be put on antibiotics right away. Our bodies were covered in painful bite wounds and abscess wounds, and I had scars from previous bite marks on my face and underbelly.  

Despite everything I went through, I am a sweet and caring pup who loves spending time with humans. I am a loyal girl who will watch over your every movement. I am very comfortable with women but require a little more patience from men. If you are nice it won’t take me long to warm up to you! I haven’t had much experience with children, but I seem to be afraid of them. 

I am a very good girl inside the house and do well when left home alone. However, I take my outside time very seriously and might bark, pace, or scratch at the door when I am ready for some fresh air. Once outside I enjoy the occasional sunbath, but really, it’s a place for me to find exciting new things to add to my collections.   

I tend to be reactive to all types of excitement, especially other animals. If there is wildlife on the other side of the fence, I will let you know it. I’ve never been one to back down from chasing a cat and I’ve heard rumors you should keep them away from me. When I see unfamiliar dogs, my instincts are to stare them down and stiffen my muscles. I will guard my food and toys from other dogs and snap or snarl at them if they appear to want what I have. 

Unfortunately, excitement isn’t the best thing for me. I have hip dysplasia and while I am strong, I require a home with a sedentary lifestyle. I shouldn’t go to dog parks, or on long walks or hikes to keep my hips in good shape.  I should be the only dog unless the other dog is elderly and not likely to tempt me into playing rough. I am on daily joint supplements and have a prescription for medication to help when I am showing discomfort. With proper weight management, continued joint supplements, and exercise modifications I can live to be an old lady. 

I am allergic to chicken and I'm required to be on a diet with limited or no grain foods while also avoiding beef. I am an otherwise healthy and happy pup who wants nothing more than a family to share my love with. Historically, black dogs, especially black pit bulls, have been hard to adopt. If you think we would make a good match please fill out an application for adoption. I look forward to meeting you!

animal.description:
Hello! My name is Eric and I have so much love to give. I was hoping you would take a minute to get to know me and see if we could be best friends! I am a playful 2-year-old American Staffordshire Terrier/Rottweiler/Samoyed mix. I have my basic commands down and I’m eager to please. My favorite activities include cuddling with my human, playing with my squeaky toys, and winning tug-of-war.

Before you can understand who I am now, we first need to explore my past. When I was just eight weeks old, I was rescued from a hoarding situation in California with my seven sisters. We were underweight and sick and needed to be put on antibiotics right away. My face and underbody were covered in scars that I have since grown into. I was also covered in bite wounds and infections and had a huge abscess on the right side of my face that left my skin a little droopy.

As a result of my past, I tend to be a little anxious and scared at times. I am friendly, just nervous. When it comes to people, I am good with volunteers but sometimes growl at doctors when I first meet them. I am most comfortable around women, especially older women. I like men too, I just require a little patience before I warm up to them. I feel most comfortable when there are no surprises, so naturally children make me a little nervous. I may growl as they approach since I am unsure of what is going to happen; the older children are the more comfortable I am. 

I am a curious pup, but I am also very shy. Strange dogs make me nervous and I will stare them down as my muscles stiffen. My foster family would likely tell you that I seem submissive or scared of other dogs and that it would be best if I was the only dog at first. I’ve heard rumors that some dogs like to cuddle with cats, but that’s not me! I think they look like chew toys and I wouldn’t do well living in a house with one.

I love adventure, especially when it involves water! I also enjoy going for walks, but I do pull strongly on the leash. I get so excited by all the new smells I forget my manners! I always think car rides are a good idea, so I jump right in, but my nerves cause me to pant and whine sometimes making me a little carsick. I am a good boy inside the house and can be left home alone, but I do feel some separation anxiety and have been known to bark or whine. I have been successful in the past when left in a quiet room in a crate.

 I am allergic to chicken and I'm required to be on a diet with limited or no grain foods while also avoiding beef. I take fish oil supplements to help my itchy skin caused by my allergies. I am an otherwise strong and healthy boy. 

Historically, black dogs, especially black pitbulls, have been hard to adopt. I am a happy and loving pup who wants nothing more than a family of my own to create memories with. If you think we would make a good match please fill out an application for adoption. I look forward to meeting you!

animal.description:
Trixie is a shy and sweet girl. She must be adopted with Tango as they are a bonded pair.

She was brought in with her kennel mate Tango because their owner was moving.

animal.description:
Hello everyone! My name is Sabor and guess what? I am the world's sweetest dog! Here are a few basic facts about me. I am just a rescue dog and nothing fancy. I'm estimated to be around 10 years old. Looks like I am a chihuahua mix of some sort. I'm mostly black with some tan on my face and paws. I weigh about 14 pounds, and if you love me, you won't overfeed me because I sure love to eat. But I also love to take short walks and I'm great on a leash. The walks are good for me and you, and I don't pull on the leash at all. By the way, I am also great when I encounter other dogs or people.

In fact, I'm fabulous with other dogs. I live in a foster home with a bunch of other dogs and get along with everyone. I am a very laid back and low energy guy. I am crate trained and housetrained (if kept on a frequent schedule). I don't bark much either. I do have to tell you that I have several health issues and need to take medication twice a day. I take my pills very easily. Just put them in a bit of cheese or lunch meat or a pill pocket. I am very well controlled on my medication and, except for some hair loss and bigger-than-average tummy, you would never know that I have any health problems.

So you see, I'm just about perfect. I love to snuggle on your lap and I'm affectionate, but not needy. I would do great in a variety of homes. Toddlers and young children probably would not be my best match as I'm a mature fellow, but older ones are fine. I'm also adaptable and could easily enjoy life in an apartment or a house with a fenced yard. My only requirement is a loving home...Is that yours?

For inquiries, email inquiry@angelsrescue.org

An Adoption Application for this dog can be found and submitted online. http://www.angelsrescue.org/adopt/adoption-forms

animal.description:
Maui - Female -DOB -12/30/17

Beautiful, almost 3 yr old Maui appears to possibly be a mix of German short hair Pointer, Pit Bull.

A lovely spirit, gentle, a timid dog until she knows you. Very shy. Men and children terrify her.

She has the body of a Pointer, tall and lean, and the loving eyes of a Pit Bull. Her mama is a Pit Bull.

Here are a list of things that we feel Maui will need in her new home, for Maui to continue to be a happy dog.

Please read the following 6 questions. If your answers are YES to ALL of them, we encourage you to please fill out an application for Maui!

1. Do I have only females (humans) living in my/our home? (2 previous adoptions with a male in the home failed)
2. Does my home have another full time, young, playful, medium/large dog for Maui to grow old with? 
3. Is someone (female) home a lot? 
4. Am I able to continue her on the inexpensive medication Buspirone, for her fearfulness?
5. Do I have a large rural yard, securely surrounded with a wooden 6 ft tall fence? (she needs a large yard for exercise and playing fetch)
6. Do I live in a rural/country area?

Maui is a high energy dog that needs a large enough yard to burn off energy. She loves to play fetch, chew on squeaky toys and play with other large dogs. She also likes to snuggle with her human foster parents. She's a very gentle, playful, sweet -but timid dog.

For her happiness and mental health, Maui will need a home in country with a 6ft secure wooden fence, and a large yard. She enjoys having playtime in the yard to play and romp with another, medium to large dog, and to play fetch with her human.

Due to her timid behavior around people, she will need at least one other friendly, YOUNG, playful. medium to large dog to live with and grow up with. Without this, she will NOT be a happy dog, so it is a must.

City life will not work for Maui, she is too nervous for city, suburban living. All the cars and people make her extremely uncomfortable and she would have a complete meltdown. In the country, she is more comfortable. Maui will walk cautiously on a leash, but not without another canine sibling by her side. She would much rather run and play in her fenced yard with a female human, and another fun dog. A home is for Maui's best interest.

Once she knows you, she is the sweetest, cuddly, playful, gentle dog. At first she is leery of new people and will run in fear. She doesn't have a mean bone in her body, she's just nervous at first and fearful. It will take her a bit of time to become comfortable with her new humans... but once she gains your trust, she will follow you around and be your best friend.

Due to Maui's sensitive temperament, she will require multiple meets and possibly some sleep overs before adoption. We want her transition to be as smooth and easy on her as possible. 

Maui, unfortunately was NOT properly socialized at the crucial weeks of her young life that she needed to be. Because of this, she's a VERY TIMID dog around new people. She's NEVER aggressive, has never attempted to bite, she just shies away from people until she trust them... which will take time and patience.

She's such a sweet dog, she just needs the right home, one that understands this is her temperament and she is shy by nature. 

Recap:
Maui is sweet, gentle, playful and most comfortable with women,once she knows them. If she doesn't know someone, she tries to run away from them. She has never attempted to nip, she's just incredibly timid. 

She was never abused, she was raised with her mama and siblings, then surrendered to rescue because the owners couldn't afford to alter all the pups and wanted the best for them.

Maui is timid when meeting new people/places so she needs a lot of patience, by nature she has a shy temperament. Having another friendly, well balanced canine sibling will help her overcome this.

She's potty trained and crate trained, and walks pretty well on a leash, UNTIL she sees a stranger, then she becomes fearful. She will greet dogs in a calm and friendly manner, but will air snap at them if they rush her. (fear)

She's not a dog that will do well left home alone for hours. She is energetic, playful and most likely destructive if left home along and gets bored. A daycare would be too much for her.

Maui is crate trained, but prefers to share the human bed. 

Maui will do best placed in a home with another young, playful, medium/large, well balanced dog, to learn from and grow old with. A dog friendly cat would be a bonus. She tries so hard to get the cats in her foster home to be her friends.

Maui is a sensitive, timid dog by nature that wants nothing more than to please. She loves her humans and is a big cuddle bug, once she trusts. Couch and bed privileges a must, she loves to be close.

She will need a home that understands working with a timid dog. If yelled at, she will panic and run from it.

She will need a rural/country home with a large, 5-6 foot high fenced yard. She will do best with access to both inside and out, she loves being in the yard playing, but also wants to snuggle on the couch or floor near you. 

Maui is adjusting to car rides. She settles in, mainly because she's afraid. She doesn't whine, bark or pace. She will need continued help getting used to car rides. 

Our adoption process:
Application - approval
Meet and greet - approval
Home check - approval (for the safety of our rescued dogs)
ADOPTION

Adoption Fee: $250
Includes:  spay, microchip, up to date shots, worm treatments, flea treatment and one beautiful, sweet, sensitive dog

>>>>For more information or an application to adopt please email: kelley2nwac@gmail.com

animal.description:
Julius is a 10 year old labrador mixed with a bit of pit bull. He is about 60 pounds. He's a nice boy who loves being petted. He prefers female dogs and likes playing in the exercise yard with Penny, a 4 year old hound mix.
The wrinkles on the top of his head give him a bit of a sharpei look.
He has been with us a couple years and would love a home or foster.
Please find our applications and valuable information under 'Adopt a dog'* on our website: *www.beaglesandbuddies.com* and email your application to beaglesandbuddies@gmail.com. Let us know your preference of appointment day/time and which dogs you are interested in and we will do our best to accommodate and email you the closest appointment available. Please allow us up to a week to get back to you. Most appointments will be Friday-Sunday, 10 am - 2 pm, for an hour.
*Note bring any other dog/s and the entire family to your meet and greet at B&B.* A complimentary training manual is included with each adoption, authored by terristeuben.com. Check out her website - she is fabulous!
B&B is glad to be open during the pandemic. We know the value and comfort of a loving pet companion and are doing our best to help the dogs and folks who need them. We update our website daily and are always rescuing, vetting, rehabilitating, socializing.
* We are accepting applications for volunteers to spend time with our dogs, hang out, sing/read to the shy ones, walk/toss ball with those who go to the playgrounds; cleaning, office work, gardening, and building/repair projects! *
Are you my furrever family?

For further info on the adoption process, please visit our home page and check out the "Adopt a Dog" section, which has thorough instructions. All our dogs are spayed/neutered, microchipped, and

fully vaccinated before adoption; they have been wormed, bathed, socialized, walked daily and much loved; each adoptee leaves with a leash, collar, and all medical records.

Our prices are higher than the shelters' because we nurse the dogs through their illnesses and get them needed surgeries and dentals. We also spend time socializing. Furthermore, unlike shelters, rescues do not get financial aid from the government and must rely on donations, grants, and adoption fees. Our fees for adults start at $150 and go up to $750. The higher end is for our most in demand dogs, such as young beagles and other purebred dogs. The lower end is for dogs who have been here a while. For puppies, we may go beyond this and charge $1000. The good news is that, because rescues fall under the "charity" category, the fees for our dogs are officially donations and are therefore tax deductible. You can think of it as donating to a worthy cause and getting a dog in return!

Sponsor Me

Beagles & Buddies must find ways to raise money so we can continue saving dogs. Your tax-deductible donation keeps our rescue kennel operating!

Hours

Friday: 10 am to 3 pm

Saturday: 10 am to 3 pm

Sunday: 10 am to 3 pm

Monday: CLOSED

Tuesday: CLOSED

Wednesday: CLOSED

Thursday: CLOSED



Weekday appointments may be available. We are a small staff and do our best to accommodate your needs. **Note that during COVID, we are not holding open houses on any day. Please email us for an appointment and include your application (found on our website, beaglesandbuddies.com, under "Forms"). Most appointments will be Friday through Sunday, though other days may also be available. We usually schedule one appointment per hour. Allow 1-2 hours for your appointment. Please look at our website and make a list of one or more dogs that you would like to see.

Contacting Us

If you have a question about adopting, giving up a dog, boarding, or volunteering, please visit the appropriate tabs on our
home page.

For more specific questions, call 626-444-9664 (please leave a voicemail if no answer) or email at beaglesandbuddies@gmail.com. Note that
Emailing
is always preferred!

Thanks!

Please note: If you are viewing this profile anywhere other than Beagles & Buddies own website, you are not receiving full info. Visit info on pet here.

animal.description:
Hi, My name is Gunther!

I know, I don't look much like a Rottweiler, but I've got the heart of one!

I think at least one of my parents may have been a shepherd, but I'm not really certain. That's ok though, I'm a pretty cute pup if I do say so myself. I'm about 75pounds or total cuteness who would love to find a special someone I can be loyal to and hang on their every word.

So how'd I become an honorary Rottweiler you may ask?

Well, my foster mom saw me online and sent out a desperate plea to save me after finding out I was set to be euthanized because I was exposed to parvo after my kennel mate contracted it and passed away.

Just so happens my foster mom had experience with parvo pups so they were all set up to be able to take me in and provide what I needed had I ended up with parvo too. Otherwise, my chances of making it out of the shelter alive were extremely slim.

The awesome folks with Southern States Rescued Rottweilers agreed I could become an honorary rottie and worked tirelessly overnight to get all the paperwork submitted to the shelter before my deadline. The next day my foster mom came to pick me up and I was soooooooooooooo happy to see her. She had little people with her too! How lucky was I? Jackpot!

After 2 weeks in quarantine...it was very boring mind you, I never contracted parvo so I was free to be a puppy again.

I love people! Like, I really, really love people! I want to be with people as much as possible. I actually think I'm people.

See, I don't really remember my siblings or my parents. I just know people. When I came to my foster home I wasn't quite sure about all these dogs and cats that were living there too. It took me a little time to get to know them and be sure they weren't going to do me harm. I've been in my foster home for awhile now and get along really well with all my foster siblings, 4 legged and 2 legged. Well, except one, but he starts it. He does scare me though and I will get defensive sometimes. My foster family keeps us separated but they are working with both of us to overcome our fear of each other. I get it...he came from a rough situation too and I'm bigger than he is so he's just as scared of me as I am of him. We've come a long way, but still have some work to do.

I do love my foster sisters most. They really get me out and about running around and wrestling. I don't initiate it myself though. If I had a choice, I'd rather go for a walk with my foster people or just hang out with them.

They have these furry animals called cats. Have you seen these things!? I tried to get a good look at them by sticking my face in their face, but one was always hitting me so I leave her alone now. The other one is big and scary. I think he's part dog. I don't mess with him. There's a little one too. She doesn't do much but sleep so I just let her be. I'm told I'm a good dog when I do. I really like being told I'm a good dog .

Sometimes I get excited and jump up, but with the help of my foster family, I've been doing that less and less. I really just love them so much I want to be right there where they can reach me without having to bend over. Just looking out for them. I walk really well on a leash. Actually, I prefer to be walked. I like having my people beside me even when I go outside for a potty break.

I love my people and will hang on every word if you let me. I like to be guided and directed and will do very well with time and training.....VERY well! 

I also know basic commands....sit, shake, am crate trained and know how to use a doggie door.

I'd do well in a home as an only dog or with 1-2 other non dominant dogs. I'm ok with small children once I get over my initial excitement, but considering my size and that I still can't always control my jumping, I may be better suited to a family with bigger kids or in a home with dog savvy children. I also would do well in a single or coupled household who is looking for a dog to train and be a companion.

If you think you'd love to have me be a part of your family forever and can provide me that time and training that will make me become the best pup ever, please fill out an application and one of SSRR's adoption coordinators will be in contact with you. Hope to meet you soon!

animal.description:
Hello everyone, it’s me Hastings Harris and I’m here because I am looking for a new family to live with forever. If you are looking for a life-long friend, maybe we will be the perfect match.

Here’s my stats:
Possible Breed:  Lhasa Apso and Brussels Griffon
Gender:  I’m a guy, a dude, an hombre
Colors:  Cream
Age:  The vet says about 6 years young
Weight:  Around 17 pounds

Hastings is a very loving pup and he loves to play! He has had a tough road before he came to us. He was hit by a car but has fully recovered and 
has no no limitations on his activity. He was also heart worm positive when he came to us. He has been successfully treated for heart worms and is now ready for a new home. Hastings did bite when he first came to rescue so he must go to a home with no children under the age of 16. 

If you are an approved adopter, email adoptioninquiries@yahoo.com and we will arrange a meeting. If you have not yet been approved, begin an application to adopt Hastings or one of our other pups at www.shihtzu-rescue.com. 

PS. I've had ALL my vetting, and oh boy, it was a lot. Here's what I had done:
Distemper/Parvo shots – TWICE. One shot doesn't cut it.
Bordetella shots - ALSO TWICE. 
Spay/Neuter-of course.
A fecal exam so I don't have any bad worms. Treatment if I do.
A heartworm test. Treatment if I am positive for heart worms
BLOODWORK to make sure my liver and kidneys are working well, because you know, we doggies often have issues in the liver and kidneys.
A DENTAL exam AND cleaning if I needed it- yep, all my toofies are checked out.
See, that's a LOT. Ask your vet - that's a LOT.

animal.description:
"Brindee" is a very sweet and energetic, 3 year old Catahoula mix (maybe Springer Spaniel) who loves to GO!  She is spayed, current on her vaccinations, and nicely house trained.  She has been very cared for and loved, but her mom is a health care worker whose hours have increased and "Brindee" is NOT getting the exercise or attention she once was getting.  She needs room to run and an active family who will take her camping, recreating, and that has a nice large yard for her to run and play in.

"Brindee" loves to play frisby and fetch and is extremely agile.  She would be great with agility training and is smart and eager to learn.  She is crate trained, but her high energy level is just too much for her to handle being crated for long periods of time while her owner works.  She has experienced some separation issues because she has been left behind and has too much energy.  She has been living with a pitbull for several years and they play well together, but just not enough action for "Brindee."

For and application to adopt, email kathy@3dogrescue.com which can be completed online.  Her adoption fee is $200 and she will come with her complete vet records, her bedding, food, and a crate if you so desire.  We do not adopt to families with children under the age of 5 and prefer to adopt within a 200 mile radius of Cody/Powell area as we have a two week trial period before adoptions are final.

All dogs adopted through Troy Animal Rescue Project are up to date on vaccinations, spayed/neutered (age appropriate), and heartworm negative. The address for our rescue center is 34 County Road 2266, Brundidge, AL 36010. We are one turn off Hwy 167. If you use Google maps, type in Troy Animal Rescue Project and it will take you right to us. Hours of operation are from 10-3 daily. We are open Saturdays and Sundays. No appointment necessary for pets that are located at the rescue center. Appointments must be made to visit pets in foster homes. Location information will be listed beside the pets name if they are at a location other than our rescue center.

Questions can be emailed to troyanimalrescueproject@gmail.com or call 334-508-2367.

animal.description:
Hi! My name is Nova but I also answer to my previous name, Zoe. My caretakers say I’m the sweetest dog at the kennel and very special, bringing joy to those around me. They think that I might me a full-blooded Pitbull Terrier.

I love to sit on laps and be loved on, and at 70 lbs there is a lot of me to love! I like to play with stuffed animals and other dogs, but I don’t like being growled at. I’m a powerful dog but good with older kids. I prefer a home without cats. 

If I don’t know someone I may nip at them through the fence. My caretakers think I may have been kept penned up too much in my previous home, but once I’m let out of my kennel I run and play with the other dogs. I’m also housetrained.

I was about 6 years old when I came to the shelter in August, 2018. I’ve been vaccinated, dewormed, flea treated, microchipped, and will be spayed before going to my furever home.

If you’re interested in me, please come meet me and take me for a walk to get to know me!


For more information on Nova please call Sierra's Haven at 1-740-353-5100. Come visit us any time to meet and get to know our pets. All dogs will be spayed/neutered, up to date on vaccines, and tested to make sure that they are heartworm negative before the adoption process can be completed. Birth dates and ages for our pets are usually approximate. Call Sierra's Haven to make sure that the pet that you are interested in is still available for adoption and that they are ready to be adopted. Our organization offers 24PetWatch microchips, which include free registration into the 24PetWatch pet recovery service. For more information visit www.24petwatch.com or call 1-866-597-2424. This pet also is eligible for 30 days of pre-paid ShelterCare pet health insurance. For more information please visit www.sheltercare.com or call 1-866-375-PETS.

animal.description: Blizzard was a stray, brought in to shelter, traumatized, submissive.  Shelter worked with him, got him walking on leash.  Still very frightened - obviously had a bad start in life.  Transferred to Great Pyr Rescue - NE.  He will be with us until his confidence is built up.  3/13/19   UPDATE:  We ran DNA on Blizzard.  Of his eight great-grandparents, five were Pyrs.  One was Anatolian, one was Australian Shepherd, and one was Rhodesian Ridgeback!  No wonder we have a very cautious, fast-moving dog.  He has white eyelashes and double dewclaws, but otherwise, I see the Anatolian and the Ridgeback.  This boy is strong on recessive genes.  He's a love, but it takes a while for him to trust you.  Anyone adopting him will need to invest time gaining his trust, but then will have a very handsome, faithful hound.  10/20/19   Blizzard is getting sweeter every day, but still is very doubtful about strangers, especially men.  If you have patience - a good fence - and love, this guy is your special friend.  2/15/20  Blizzard still waits for his forever home - such a sweet guy.  6/1/20  STAYING IN FOSTER FOR A WHILE YET - NEEDS MORE BEHAVIOR MODIFICATION
